WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.707 --> 00:00:05.540
PROFESSOR: I'm excited
about today's lecture

00:00:05.540 --> 00:00:07.050
because there's so
many fun topics.

00:00:07.050 --> 00:00:12.790
This is like many fun
things all in one lecture.

00:00:12.790 --> 00:00:17.790
We're going to start with a
cool little problem, which

00:00:17.790 --> 00:00:20.480
is about unfolding
and re-folding.

00:00:25.656 --> 00:00:27.030
You could think
of them-- they're

00:00:27.030 --> 00:00:29.900
kind of like hinged
dissections although they're

00:00:29.900 --> 00:00:34.480
from between surfaces
of polyhedra.

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:36.980
You can also think of
them as common unfoldings.

00:00:42.610 --> 00:00:48.841
So general idea is,
you have over here

00:00:48.841 --> 00:00:56.090
in the left team you have
unfoldings-- polygons,

00:00:56.090 --> 00:00:57.640
let's say.

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:02.572
Possible things that
could fold into polyhedra.

00:01:02.572 --> 00:01:04.934
And we'll think convex again.

00:01:08.026 --> 00:01:09.775
And when we were
thinking about unfolding,

00:01:09.775 --> 00:01:11.650
we we're thinking about
going this direction.

00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:13.230
When we were thinking
about folding,

00:01:13.230 --> 00:01:14.850
we were thinking
about this direction.

00:01:14.850 --> 00:01:17.720
But what if we do
both repeatedly?

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:20.290
So I start, say, with a cube.

00:01:20.290 --> 00:01:23.069
And then I unfold it
and then I re-fold it.

00:01:23.069 --> 00:01:25.110
That's sort of what the
metamorphosis of the cube

00:01:25.110 --> 00:01:27.060
was about.

00:01:27.060 --> 00:01:29.143
And then I unfold
that and I re-fold it,

00:01:29.143 --> 00:01:31.860
and I unfold and I re-fold
and I unfold and re-fold.

00:01:31.860 --> 00:01:34.520
This is a fun tour to take.

00:01:34.520 --> 00:01:36.190
Is this space connected?

00:01:36.190 --> 00:01:38.530
Can I get from any
polyhedral surface

00:01:38.530 --> 00:01:41.580
to any other-- say, convex--
by unfolding and re-folding?

00:01:41.580 --> 00:01:43.820
We have no idea.

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:45.460
So while each of
these operations

00:01:45.460 --> 00:01:48.430
we know a fair amount about--
we know how to generally unfold

00:01:48.430 --> 00:01:51.640
convex polyhedra,
we know how to find

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:55.790
all of the gluings of a polygon
into a polyhedron-- repeating

00:01:55.790 --> 00:01:58.050
those processes,
we could explore

00:01:58.050 --> 00:02:02.120
but actually no ones' every
tried that algorithmically.

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:05.830
It'd be fun to see what
crazy things you get.

00:02:05.830 --> 00:02:09.870
But we have lots of examples
and partial progress

00:02:09.870 --> 00:02:12.360
towards this question.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:13.660
So here's the first example.

00:02:13.660 --> 00:02:15.540
This appears in the book.

00:02:15.540 --> 00:02:17.660
It's by Hirata from 2000.

00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:21.710
He was one of the guys who
implemented a gluing algorithm.

00:02:21.710 --> 00:02:26.630
And this is an unfolding--
a common unfolding--

00:02:26.630 --> 00:02:32.120
of a cube-- ah, not quite--
and a regular tetrahedron.

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:34.520
So it's actually
a box not a cube.

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:36.470
One of the big open
questions in this area

00:02:36.470 --> 00:02:39.420
is, can you find
a common unfolding

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:45.506
of a perfect cube and a regular
tetrahedron that's open?

00:02:45.506 --> 00:02:46.880
Marty posed that
question I think

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:52.270
in 1998, in the good old days of
the beginning of folding stuff.

00:02:52.270 --> 00:02:56.040
And this is almost an answer
but it's not quite a cube,

00:02:56.040 --> 00:02:56.750
as a result.

00:02:56.750 --> 00:02:58.708
You could see-- I think
it's pretty easy to see

00:02:58.708 --> 00:03:03.230
how to fold it into a box just
with extending all the lines.

00:03:03.230 --> 00:03:04.990
And the dotted lines
show how to fold

00:03:04.990 --> 00:03:06.185
into a regular tetrahedron.

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:10.880
That's one example.

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:16.930
You can also fold-- this thing
makes both a regular octahedron

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:22.280
instead of a regular tetrahedron
and some kind of tetrahedra.

00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:23.200
It's not regular.

00:03:23.200 --> 00:03:26.290
We call it a tetramonohedron,
meaning each of the sides

00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:27.930
are the same.

00:03:27.930 --> 00:03:31.380
So it's just one type of side,
but there's four of them.

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:34.670
And I guess the red lines
are folding into that,

00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:37.210
the green lines fold into
a regular tetrahedron.

00:03:40.350 --> 00:03:41.910
I feel like I'm
getting forgetful.

00:03:41.910 --> 00:03:43.830
I don't even remember where
this example comes from.

00:03:43.830 --> 00:03:45.955
But it's in the book, it's
not attributed to anyone

00:03:45.955 --> 00:03:49.310
so I assume Joe invented it.

00:03:49.310 --> 00:03:51.810
But recently, like
just this year,

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:54.880
inspired a whole bunch of
examples by these guys.

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:57.370
I just saw the talk
last week in China--

00:03:57.370 --> 00:04:00.180
that's where I was traveling,
it was a geometry conference.

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:03.710
And Horiyama and Uehara
talked about a bunch

00:04:03.710 --> 00:04:06.030
of different common unfoldings.

00:04:06.030 --> 00:04:07.780
This is, again, of
a regular octahedron

00:04:07.780 --> 00:04:09.230
and a tetramonohedron.

00:04:09.230 --> 00:04:11.030
But a different example.

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:12.040
But they kept going.

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:14.210
Said all right, let's do
all the platonic solids.

00:04:14.210 --> 00:04:17.990
So this is a common unfolding
of a cube and a tetramonohedron.

00:04:17.990 --> 00:04:19.800
Cube-- actually two of them.

00:04:19.800 --> 00:04:21.480
You can see how it makes a cube.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:22.740
That's obvious.

00:04:22.740 --> 00:04:26.180
But the tetramonohedron
are the blue lines.

00:04:26.180 --> 00:04:30.590
Then I have the octahedron,
we have the icosahedron.

00:04:30.590 --> 00:04:32.440
I don't think they
have a dodecahedron yet

00:04:32.440 --> 00:04:35.530
because all of these
approaches are actually

00:04:35.530 --> 00:04:37.530
based on dissection
techniques where

00:04:37.530 --> 00:04:42.330
you take a tiling of-- here
are equilateral triangles

00:04:42.330 --> 00:04:43.990
for the icosahedron,
and you take

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:47.610
a tiling of some
triangle that's going

00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:50.395
to make the tetramonohedron,
and you align them

00:04:50.395 --> 00:04:53.010
so that things work out nicely.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:54.480
And that's not
always well defined,

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:56.120
but it often leads
to good dissections,

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:57.942
often hinged dissections.

00:04:57.942 --> 00:04:59.400
It's the way, for
example, you show

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:00.940
you can hinge
dissect a rectangle

00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:02.100
into any other rectangle.

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:03.880
You take tilings of
different rectangles

00:05:03.880 --> 00:05:06.120
and overlay them appropriately.

00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:09.190
Here, same approach,
but with a dodecahedron,

00:05:09.190 --> 00:05:10.900
regular pentagons
don't tile so it's

00:05:10.900 --> 00:05:13.110
very hard to use that approach.

00:05:13.110 --> 00:05:15.329
So this is as far
as they've gotten.

00:05:15.329 --> 00:05:16.870
Here they've measured
the proportions

00:05:16.870 --> 00:05:18.780
of the tetramonohedron
to give you an idea.

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:20.320
It's close to regular.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:22.900
But again, open question,
can any two platonic solids--

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:26.100
do any two have a
common unfolding?

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:29.680
They proved in this paper,
if you restrict one of them

00:05:29.680 --> 00:05:32.870
to be an edge unfolding
and the other one

00:05:32.870 --> 00:05:35.170
can be a general unfolding
then it's not possible.

00:05:35.170 --> 00:05:37.880
But if they're both general
unfoldings, who knows.

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:42.170
Here you see it's edge
unfolding for the icosahedron,

00:05:42.170 --> 00:05:44.190
but general unfolding
for the other.

00:05:46.575 --> 00:05:47.075
Cool.

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:51.540
But very recently,
this is, like,

00:05:51.540 --> 00:05:52.990
hasn't even been released yet.

00:05:52.990 --> 00:05:57.840
This is the premier
of the following,

00:05:57.840 --> 00:05:59.190
I'll call it conjecture.

00:05:59.190 --> 00:06:02.930
I think it's not yet
approved or explicitly-- it's

00:06:02.930 --> 00:06:04.180
not certain that it's correct.

00:06:04.180 --> 00:06:08.204
But the claim is this gray
shape, taken to the limit--

00:06:08.204 --> 00:06:10.120
so this is the first
iteration of the fractal,

00:06:10.120 --> 00:06:13.510
this is the second iteration
of the fractal-- in the limit,

00:06:13.510 --> 00:06:19.040
will fold both to a regular
tetrahedron and a cube.

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:21.750
This would be an
amazing breakthrough.

00:06:21.750 --> 00:06:23.830
Still, the conjecture
is that it is not

00:06:23.830 --> 00:06:25.570
possible to go from
a regular tetrahedron

00:06:25.570 --> 00:06:28.335
to a cube with a regular--
like a normal polygon

00:06:28.335 --> 00:06:30.100
with a finite number of sides.

00:06:30.100 --> 00:06:33.530
But with an infinite number of
sides, it seems to be possible.

00:06:33.530 --> 00:06:35.500
Which is awesome.

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:38.320
This is-- I haven't
met this guy yet.

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:41.940
He's a professional puzzler
in Japan, Toshihiro Shirakawa.

00:06:44.650 --> 00:06:52.480
So stay tuned for maybe a proof
of that theorem, that claim.

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:54.730
The next topic--
this started back

00:06:54.730 --> 00:06:57.700
in '99, inspired
by this question.

00:06:57.700 --> 00:07:01.240
We thought well,
what about boxes?

00:07:01.240 --> 00:07:06.067
And this is a common unfolding
of two different size boxes

00:07:06.067 --> 00:07:06.650
which is cool.

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:09.040
And it's generated in
a fairly intuitive way.

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:10.690
You start with an
unfolding of a box.

00:07:10.690 --> 00:07:13.632
This makes a one
by one by three box

00:07:13.632 --> 00:07:15.340
if you think about it
for a little while.

00:07:15.340 --> 00:07:18.400
Just wrap around-- this
is like one top side, 1

00:07:18.400 --> 00:07:21.380
by 3 rectangle and wrap around.

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:24.240
And then you-- you
draw the gluing-- here

00:07:24.240 --> 00:07:26.690
I've labeled which edges
glue to which edges.

00:07:26.690 --> 00:07:29.010
And for every letter,
like the two Gs

00:07:29.010 --> 00:07:32.250
here, I could imagine adding a
triangle here and removing it

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:33.450
from here.

00:07:33.450 --> 00:07:36.400
That will still fold to
the same thing, right?

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:39.790
So I get to choose
for each letter which

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:42.370
guy goes in, which guy goes out.

00:07:42.370 --> 00:07:46.080
Then I get this shape as
a result of that process.

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:50.210
And if I do it right,
when I rotate 45 degrees,

00:07:50.210 --> 00:07:53.475
I get a different orthogonal
unfolding of some other box.

00:07:53.475 --> 00:07:55.350
So here, if I started
with a root 2 by root 2

00:07:55.350 --> 00:07:59.530
by three root 2 box, I
get a 1 by 2 by 4 box.

00:07:59.530 --> 00:08:02.450
So this is a common
unfolding of both.

00:08:02.450 --> 00:08:05.680
I guess here is like the
center core of the 1 by 2 by 4

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:07.570
and you wrap around again.

00:08:07.570 --> 00:08:10.994
Or this is probably center core.

00:08:10.994 --> 00:08:11.910
So that's pretty cool.

00:08:11.910 --> 00:08:13.810
This is an idea by Timothy Chan.

00:08:13.810 --> 00:08:15.330
Of course, natural
question is, do I

00:08:15.330 --> 00:08:19.420
need to do this rotation trick
or could I get away without it?

00:08:19.420 --> 00:08:21.060
And you can get away without it.

00:08:21.060 --> 00:08:23.250
This is an idea
of Therese Biedl.

00:08:23.250 --> 00:08:25.390
This is my Waterloo days.

00:08:25.390 --> 00:08:28.250
We had an open problem
session, kind of like the one

00:08:28.250 --> 00:08:29.740
we have in this class.

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:32.070
It was the very
first one that I ran.

00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:33.370
I ran it with Therese.

00:08:33.370 --> 00:08:36.270
And she came up with this idea.

00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:39.159
This is a-- it's not obvious
exactly how this works

00:08:39.159 --> 00:08:40.831
or where she came up with this.

00:08:40.831 --> 00:08:41.789
It was kind of magical.

00:08:41.789 --> 00:08:44.790
But this the same polygon,
different creases, you

00:08:44.790 --> 00:08:46.260
make two different size boxes.

00:08:46.260 --> 00:08:48.890
Now they're going to be integers
because they're orthogonal

00:08:48.890 --> 00:08:51.910
aligned on the grid.

00:08:51.910 --> 00:08:52.670
Pretty cool.

00:08:52.670 --> 00:08:55.050
And for a long time, this
was the only example of this

00:08:55.050 --> 00:08:56.860
that we had.

00:08:56.860 --> 00:09:00.660
There's still an open question
which I give you A by C by-- A

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:05.100
by B by C box and a D by E
by F box, is this possible?

00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:07.140
When is this possible?

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:10.470
But at least now--
oh, here's, sorry.

00:09:10.470 --> 00:09:12.950
There are two examples.

00:09:12.950 --> 00:09:15.950
Of course, the surface
areas have to match.

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:19.450
So the sum of A plus B plus
C equals D plus E plus F.

00:09:19.450 --> 00:09:20.465
I think that's right.

00:09:20.465 --> 00:09:21.194
Or no.

00:09:21.194 --> 00:09:22.110
It's more complicated.

00:09:22.110 --> 00:09:26.010
It's like A times
B plus-- and so on.

00:09:26.010 --> 00:09:27.382
Pairwise products.

00:09:27.382 --> 00:09:28.840
Now we know that
there are actually

00:09:28.840 --> 00:09:30.130
infinitely many examples.

00:09:30.130 --> 00:09:35.020
This is another fairly
new result by Uehara,

00:09:35.020 --> 00:09:37.200
again in 2008.

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:40.030
This is-- Uehara translated
our textbook to Japanese,

00:09:40.030 --> 00:09:41.100
by the way.

00:09:41.100 --> 00:09:42.340
Another connection.

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:44.340
He does a lot of
fun folding stuff.

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:46.480
Just saw him last week.

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:48.650
So this is an
example of taking a 1

00:09:48.650 --> 00:09:53.020
by 5 by 2k box and a common
unfolding of that with a 1

00:09:53.020 --> 00:09:55.275
by 1 by 6k plus 2 box.

00:09:55.275 --> 00:09:58.740
Which has a very
regular pattern.

00:09:58.740 --> 00:10:01.820
And this one, little more
complicated to copy and paste

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:05.990
but it makes 1 by 1 by 8k
plus 11 box and a 1 by 3

00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:08.040
by 4k plus 5 box.

00:10:08.040 --> 00:10:09.814
Which is pretty cool.

00:10:09.814 --> 00:10:11.230
I haven't studied
these carefully,

00:10:11.230 --> 00:10:15.602
but there's two different
ways to fold each.

00:10:15.602 --> 00:10:17.060
So now we know
there are infinitely

00:10:17.060 --> 00:10:18.350
many of these examples.

00:10:18.350 --> 00:10:20.320
It's still not known
when it's possible,

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:24.330
but also in this
paper Uehara came up

00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:26.911
with a sort of random
generation algorithm

00:10:26.911 --> 00:10:28.660
where he would take a
box, randomly unfold

00:10:28.660 --> 00:10:30.530
it, try to fold it
into other boxes.

00:10:30.530 --> 00:10:37.320
And he has now over 250,000
examples of this process.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:41.530
And I think these are maybe
inspired by his random search.

00:10:41.530 --> 00:10:44.330
I'm not sure, but this
is theory obviously.

00:10:44.330 --> 00:10:46.030
One particularly fun
example, this one

00:10:46.030 --> 00:10:47.492
actually tiles the plane.

00:10:47.492 --> 00:10:49.200
So it'd be efficient
if you're cutting it

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:51.400
out of sheet material.

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:54.320
You can make a common unfolding
of 1 by 2 by 5 box and a 1

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:55.810
by 1 by 8 box.

00:10:55.810 --> 00:10:59.750
I think this one he
made into a puzzle

00:10:59.750 --> 00:11:02.526
with a paper manufacturer.

00:11:02.526 --> 00:11:03.890
I'm getting ahead of myself.

00:11:03.890 --> 00:11:06.890
Big open question
here that he asked is,

00:11:06.890 --> 00:11:11.790
are there-- is there a common
unfolding of three boxes?

00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:12.770
That remains open.

00:11:12.770 --> 00:11:14.830
And he feels like he's
very close to finding one

00:11:14.830 --> 00:11:17.570
with his random search
but hasn't yet found one.

00:11:17.570 --> 00:11:20.740
It's like it almost
folds into the third box.

00:11:20.740 --> 00:11:22.990
But it's strange how
hard it is to find them.

00:11:22.990 --> 00:11:23.950
Maybe they don't exist.

00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:27.310
That would be surprising.

00:11:27.310 --> 00:11:29.430
All right.

00:11:29.430 --> 00:11:35.570
Next example on this theme,
common unfoldings, is this toy.

00:11:35.570 --> 00:11:40.950
So this is a 1 by 1 by 4 box,
also known as the-- as a tetra

00:11:40.950 --> 00:11:43.980
cubes, four cubes
joined edge to edge.

00:11:43.980 --> 00:11:48.480
And-- oh, I should
have practiced.

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:51.160
You can unfold it.

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:53.340
This is a commercially
produced toy.

00:11:53.340 --> 00:11:55.930
It's called Cubigami.

00:11:55.930 --> 00:12:00.210
And it's one net, one unfolding.

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:03.100
But it can fold into
all tetra cubes.

00:12:03.100 --> 00:12:08.560
So that was the tube and, let's
see, what else can I make here?

00:12:13.870 --> 00:12:14.875
I should have practiced.

00:12:20.070 --> 00:12:22.840
Interesting.

00:12:22.840 --> 00:12:23.840
It's fun.

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:25.550
You can play with it later.

00:12:25.550 --> 00:12:28.200
Oh, that looks interesting.

00:12:28.200 --> 00:12:28.700
Almost.

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:31.870
Not quite.

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:34.900
It's almost-- it looks
like a Tetris piece, right?

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:39.140
Except I didn't quite
cover it right at the end.

00:12:39.140 --> 00:12:41.220
It's a good puzzle.

00:12:41.220 --> 00:12:42.930
Obviously.

00:12:42.930 --> 00:12:46.830
Maybe if I do it like--
that doesn't work.

00:12:46.830 --> 00:12:47.540
Wow.

00:12:47.540 --> 00:12:48.040
All right.

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:50.310
You're going to have to
play with it yourself.

00:12:50.310 --> 00:12:51.980
I lose.

00:12:51.980 --> 00:12:56.970
But you can make all of
the four cube joinings

00:12:56.970 --> 00:13:06.595
except-- except for this one.

00:13:09.344 --> 00:13:10.760
See, the problem
with this example

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:13.430
is it doesn't have the same
surface areas the rest.

00:13:13.430 --> 00:13:15.710
And you have to
conserve surface area.

00:13:15.710 --> 00:13:17.570
But if you think about
all the other four

00:13:17.570 --> 00:13:24.240
cubes-- like I was trying to
make this guy or this guy--

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:31.580
it's like Tetris
pieces-- but also things

00:13:31.580 --> 00:13:34.484
like-- I can draw
better than I can

00:13:34.484 --> 00:13:35.650
solve the puzzle apparently.

00:13:38.330 --> 00:13:39.000
Like this.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.240
This is the one non-planar one.

00:13:45.713 --> 00:13:47.710
All right?

00:13:47.710 --> 00:13:50.045
So you've got all the Tetris
pieces except this guy.

00:13:50.045 --> 00:13:51.320
It's the wrong surface area.

00:13:51.320 --> 00:13:53.660
So, in general, it's
all the tree shape ones.

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:55.445
No cycles.

00:13:55.445 --> 00:13:56.320
Can make all of them.

00:13:56.320 --> 00:14:01.870
This is an example found by
Donald Knuth, famous computer

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:03.120
scientist.

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:07.310
He sort of accidentally
at a cocktail party heard

00:14:07.310 --> 00:14:10.770
about this problem from George
Miller who's a toy designer--

00:14:10.770 --> 00:14:13.800
or puzzle designer.

00:14:13.800 --> 00:14:16.020
And so then Knuth
went back and he

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:19.010
wrote a program to numerate
all unfoldings of these things

00:14:19.010 --> 00:14:21.410
and found there are a whole
bunch of common unfoldings.

00:14:21.410 --> 00:14:23.350
But it's found by
exhaustive search.

00:14:23.350 --> 00:14:26.750
This was the one that sort of
had the smallest bounding box,

00:14:26.750 --> 00:14:28.740
I believe, in terms of area.

00:14:28.740 --> 00:14:30.809
And so it's a nice
compact thing.

00:14:30.809 --> 00:14:32.850
And then there are various
manufacturing's of it.

00:14:32.850 --> 00:14:35.640
This is the latest one that's
sort of relatively easy

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:36.760
to build I guess.

00:14:36.760 --> 00:14:40.660
So, play with that later.

00:14:40.660 --> 00:14:42.090
That's four cubes.

00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:45.050
What about five cubes?

00:14:45.050 --> 00:14:48.920
Well, that was the subject
of a paper also presented

00:14:48.920 --> 00:14:51.340
last week in China.

00:14:51.340 --> 00:14:54.620
And it turns out, there
is no common unfolding

00:14:54.620 --> 00:14:57.770
of all 24 pentacubes.

00:14:57.770 --> 00:14:59.540
That's five cubes
joined together.

00:14:59.540 --> 00:15:05.280
But there is a common unfolding
of 23 out of 24 of them.

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:06.220
So this is the paper.

00:15:06.220 --> 00:15:07.810
There was a bunch of authors.

00:15:07.810 --> 00:15:11.030
There were basically
three teams that

00:15:11.030 --> 00:15:14.180
worked on this, two of
which were writing code.

00:15:14.180 --> 00:15:15.819
I was on one of
the coding teams.

00:15:15.819 --> 00:15:17.360
And the third one
was trying to think

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:20.370
about the problem
using mathematics.

00:15:20.370 --> 00:15:22.805
And for a long time, the
thinkers were leading.

00:15:22.805 --> 00:15:24.680
But then, of course,
eventually the computers

00:15:24.680 --> 00:15:29.100
win because after a couple days
of just solid computation on I

00:15:29.100 --> 00:15:32.000
don't know now how many cores
with each of the groups,

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.170
we numerated all
these unfoldings.

00:15:34.170 --> 00:15:40.570
And so now there's, I think,
over one trillion unfoldings

00:15:40.570 --> 00:15:43.320
of the 1 by 1 by 5 tube.

00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:45.960
But one trillions not that bad.

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:48.542
Now, we could not
do this for six.

00:15:48.542 --> 00:15:52.070
But for five it wasn't so bad.

00:15:52.070 --> 00:15:55.410
And this is-- there's a bunch
of unfoldings of 23 out of 24.

00:15:55.410 --> 00:15:57.150
But that's the max you can get.

00:15:57.150 --> 00:15:58.220
Little disappointing.

00:15:58.220 --> 00:16:00.115
AUDIENCE: Which pentacube lost?

00:16:00.115 --> 00:16:01.990
PROFESSOR: I don't know
which pentacube lost.

00:16:01.990 --> 00:16:03.090
I should find out.

00:16:03.090 --> 00:16:05.580
That's a good question.

00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:07.260
But I do have some
other answers.

00:16:07.260 --> 00:16:09.550
So in some sense,
the hard ones I think

00:16:09.550 --> 00:16:11.180
are the non-planar guys.

00:16:11.180 --> 00:16:12.950
Like this guy.

00:16:12.950 --> 00:16:15.180
So they're planar
if all the cubes

00:16:15.180 --> 00:16:18.900
lie in a thickened
plane, thickened by one.

00:16:18.900 --> 00:16:22.180
This guy will fold into
all the non-planar cubes

00:16:22.180 --> 00:16:25.670
and also fold into
most of the pentacubes.

00:16:25.670 --> 00:16:28.110
There are only 24 total
so it's only missing two.

00:16:28.110 --> 00:16:30.310
And this'll fold into
all the non-planar guys.

00:16:30.310 --> 00:16:32.330
And what's cool is
this one is unique.

00:16:32.330 --> 00:16:36.210
There's only one common
unfolding of those guys.

00:16:36.210 --> 00:16:38.022
AUDIENCE: How many
non-planar [INAUDIBLE]?

00:16:38.022 --> 00:16:39.730
PROFESSOR: How many
non-planar are there?

00:16:39.730 --> 00:16:41.700
I don't remember.

00:16:41.700 --> 00:16:43.940
Maybe 10.

00:16:43.940 --> 00:16:46.680
I think it's a minority.

00:16:46.680 --> 00:16:48.180
But there are still
a bunch of them.

00:16:48.180 --> 00:16:49.929
And I think this would
make a good puzzle.

00:16:49.929 --> 00:16:52.075
If you're going to
manufacture-- if you guys want

00:16:52.075 --> 00:16:54.670
to do a start up, here you go.

00:16:54.670 --> 00:16:57.820
Freely available.

00:16:57.820 --> 00:16:59.800
If you want to do
the planar pentacubes

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:02.430
there are a lot of common
unfoldings of them.

00:17:02.430 --> 00:17:04.780
This is one of the
fairly compact ones.

00:17:04.780 --> 00:17:07.186
And this one, I have
an animation of.

00:17:07.186 --> 00:17:08.560
Or, actually, not
this particular

00:17:08.560 --> 00:17:11.130
unfolding, but this concept.

00:17:11.130 --> 00:17:12.359
And that is here.

00:17:14.946 --> 00:17:16.839
Yes, I trust myself.

00:17:16.839 --> 00:17:20.270
So here is unfolding
and re-folding

00:17:20.270 --> 00:17:21.859
of that particular shape.

00:17:21.859 --> 00:17:23.849
And then I hit
Space bar and it's

00:17:23.849 --> 00:17:28.260
the same unfolding but
a different polycube.

00:17:28.260 --> 00:17:32.470
And this is going to go
through all of the flat ones.

00:17:32.470 --> 00:17:34.930
And that animation is
done heuristically.

00:17:34.930 --> 00:17:38.520
I don't have any theory
that that's always possible.

00:17:38.520 --> 00:17:40.630
But always keeping
the same unfolding,

00:17:40.630 --> 00:17:42.986
just changing where
the creases are.

00:17:42.986 --> 00:17:43.610
That's so cool.

00:17:47.416 --> 00:17:48.290
It's funny, actually.

00:17:48.290 --> 00:17:51.850
The person who implemented this
was the guy who was thinking,

00:17:51.850 --> 00:17:54.340
not the coder-- coder teams.

00:17:54.340 --> 00:17:55.510
I guess he had free time.

00:17:58.732 --> 00:18:00.190
This is by [? Karim ?]
[INAUDIBLE].

00:18:03.380 --> 00:18:06.357
I guess you can count them
and then subtract from 24

00:18:06.357 --> 00:18:08.440
and you'll get how many
non-planar ones there are.

00:18:08.440 --> 00:18:12.150
But I've lost track
of where we are.

00:18:12.150 --> 00:18:13.580
Always same unfolding.

00:18:13.580 --> 00:18:15.494
This is a fairly nice,
simple unfolding.

00:18:15.494 --> 00:18:16.660
It's mostly one dimensional.

00:18:20.270 --> 00:18:20.840
All right.

00:18:20.840 --> 00:18:23.500
You get the idea, right?

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:25.830
Pretty fun.

00:18:25.830 --> 00:18:27.840
All right.

00:18:27.840 --> 00:18:31.990
So, right.

00:18:31.990 --> 00:18:33.110
Do I have anymore?

00:18:33.110 --> 00:18:35.450
I think that was the
end of my slides.

00:18:35.450 --> 00:18:38.510
I do have one more example in
the notes which is, if you just

00:18:38.510 --> 00:18:43.200
want to make the flat
guys-- so just the two

00:18:43.200 --> 00:18:47.030
dimensional
examples-- so we know

00:18:47.030 --> 00:18:52.040
we could do that with five,
but you can also do with six.

00:18:52.040 --> 00:18:55.440
We wrote another
program that looks

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:58.150
at a very special
kind of unfolding.

00:18:58.150 --> 00:19:01.690
And in that special class,
it's possible to fold

00:19:01.690 --> 00:19:05.060
all planar six
cubes-- hexacubes.

00:19:05.060 --> 00:19:11.700
But that class does not work
for septacubes-- seven cubes.

00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:13.730
Open question, is there
a common unfolding

00:19:13.730 --> 00:19:17.030
of all planar seven cubes or
all non-planar seven cubes?

00:19:17.030 --> 00:19:18.440
Or how many can you make?

00:19:18.440 --> 00:19:23.475
There it was beyond exhaustion,
and we have to actually think.

00:19:23.475 --> 00:19:25.350
Unless you come up with
a good class and then

00:19:25.350 --> 00:19:27.870
you can exhaust
it in that class.

00:19:27.870 --> 00:19:31.740
One nice open question here
is, if you go to large N,

00:19:31.740 --> 00:19:35.600
are there some two polycubes
that have no common unfolding?

00:19:35.600 --> 00:19:37.180
At the moment, it
could be every pair

00:19:37.180 --> 00:19:39.170
of polycubes has a
common unfolding.

00:19:39.170 --> 00:19:40.870
Certainly there
are-- for example,

00:19:40.870 --> 00:19:43.020
in this class there
are four polycubes that

00:19:43.020 --> 00:19:45.260
do not have a common unfolding.

00:19:45.260 --> 00:19:48.370
I think we're not
sure about three.

00:19:48.370 --> 00:19:50.475
For size five.

00:19:50.475 --> 00:19:52.350
Of course, we don't even
know whether there's

00:19:52.350 --> 00:19:55.634
any polycube that
has no unfolding.

00:19:55.634 --> 00:19:56.800
I think there should be one.

00:19:56.800 --> 00:19:58.870
But at the moment, it
could be every polycube

00:19:58.870 --> 00:20:00.040
has an unfolding.

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:02.470
But to make it a little harder,
what about two polycubes

00:20:02.470 --> 00:20:04.382
at once you want a
common unfolding?

00:20:04.382 --> 00:20:05.590
All these questions are open.

00:20:08.410 --> 00:20:09.810
All right.

00:20:09.810 --> 00:20:11.510
This is common unfolding.

00:20:11.510 --> 00:20:15.840
We're going to stick
with unfolding stuff

00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:18.550
but change around the
problem a little bit.

00:20:18.550 --> 00:20:21.790
So let me ask you a question.

00:20:21.790 --> 00:20:25.540
Can have a vote for those who
haven't read the notes already

00:20:25.540 --> 00:20:28.700
and know the answer.

00:20:28.700 --> 00:20:33.510
So let's say,
orthogonal polyhedron.

00:20:33.510 --> 00:20:36.270
We talk a lot about
orthogonal polyhedra.

00:20:36.270 --> 00:20:41.790
See all this polycube
stuff is in that genre.

00:20:41.790 --> 00:20:44.480
And so way back when we
talked about grid unfolding

00:20:44.480 --> 00:20:46.820
of orthogonal polyhedra.

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:48.502
It's not known whether
that's possible,

00:20:48.502 --> 00:20:49.960
but we have epsilon
unfolding where

00:20:49.960 --> 00:20:52.580
you cut exponentially
many times and so on.

00:20:52.580 --> 00:20:56.100
But how do you define
orthogonal polyhedra?

00:20:56.100 --> 00:20:58.520
There are two
natural definitions.

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:01.820
One is that the
angles are right.

00:21:05.410 --> 00:21:08.615
Right angles, let's
say, in the faces.

00:21:11.550 --> 00:21:15.560
The other natural definition
is that you look at two faces

00:21:15.560 --> 00:21:18.320
and the angles between
those should be right.

00:21:23.845 --> 00:21:25.220
So I guess right
dihedral angles.

00:21:30.080 --> 00:21:31.985
Right face angles or
right dihedral angles.

00:21:31.985 --> 00:21:36.830
The question is, are
these the same thing?

00:21:36.830 --> 00:21:39.830
Who thinks yes?

00:21:39.830 --> 00:21:41.431
Who thinks no?

00:21:41.431 --> 00:21:41.930
Yeah.

00:21:41.930 --> 00:21:42.950
I kind of set it up.

00:21:42.950 --> 00:21:45.935
Everyone thinks no.

00:21:45.935 --> 00:21:46.810
They're not the same.

00:21:49.480 --> 00:21:53.720
But for genus zero
polyhedra, they are the same.

00:21:53.720 --> 00:21:55.990
That's maybe the
surprising thing.

00:21:55.990 --> 00:22:01.180
This is a genus
eight polyhedron.

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:02.450
No, seven.

00:22:02.450 --> 00:22:05.950
It's always a little
tricky to measure genus.

00:22:05.950 --> 00:22:09.950
If it just had one triangular
face that would be-- well,

00:22:09.950 --> 00:22:12.410
anyway, that's genus seven.

00:22:12.410 --> 00:22:14.704
I'm not going to
try to convince you.

00:22:14.704 --> 00:22:16.120
This is an unfolding
of the thing.

00:22:16.120 --> 00:22:17.647
So you can see,
in the unfolding,

00:22:17.647 --> 00:22:19.480
it looks like it's an
orthogonal polyhedron.

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:20.580
All the angles are right.

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:21.550
It looks perfect.

00:22:21.550 --> 00:22:24.000
And yet, it folds into
this non-orthogonal thing.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.740
Kind of a thickened octahedron.

00:22:27.740 --> 00:22:32.960
It's kind of critical that it
has a genus more than zero.

00:22:32.960 --> 00:22:34.940
In this paper-- this
is the original paper

00:22:34.940 --> 00:22:42.210
that considered this problem--
there's a lower bound of one.

00:22:42.210 --> 00:22:45.110
The genus 0 is not enough.

00:22:45.110 --> 00:22:50.730
Then we came along-- I don't
have the author list here.

00:22:50.730 --> 00:22:56.370
It's with the Waterloo gang, it
was Therese Biedl and others.

00:22:56.370 --> 00:23:03.050
And this is a smaller genus,
a genus six polyhedron.

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:03.760
This guy.

00:23:03.760 --> 00:23:06.540
So it's almost the same
example turned inside out.

00:23:06.540 --> 00:23:09.210
So this like to half
octahedra and then joined

00:23:09.210 --> 00:23:11.230
in this cubicle frame
and then you put caps

00:23:11.230 --> 00:23:14.990
on the cubicle frame to make
there not be holes out there.

00:23:14.990 --> 00:23:17.120
And then you have
slightly smaller genus

00:23:17.120 --> 00:23:20.610
because you can go
around the backside.

00:23:20.610 --> 00:23:22.830
So that's the best known,
is a genus six example.

00:23:22.830 --> 00:23:25.770
We proved that you need
genus at least three

00:23:25.770 --> 00:23:28.031
in order for such
an example to exist.

00:23:28.031 --> 00:23:30.030
I have a little sketch
of the proof in the notes

00:23:30.030 --> 00:23:31.650
if you want to read it.

00:23:31.650 --> 00:23:34.610
It's a fun little boot
strapping argument but I would--

00:23:34.610 --> 00:23:36.740
I'm going to go on
to other fun topics

00:23:36.740 --> 00:23:39.810
here rather than prove this.

00:23:39.810 --> 00:23:41.589
Is that a good plan?

00:23:41.589 --> 00:23:42.630
I think that's good plan.

00:23:45.830 --> 00:23:46.330
OK.

00:23:46.330 --> 00:23:48.060
So this is a fun
kind of-- unfoldings

00:23:48.060 --> 00:23:51.430
can be orthogonal while the
three dimensional versions are

00:23:51.430 --> 00:23:52.055
not orthogonal.

00:23:55.300 --> 00:23:56.550
All right.

00:23:56.550 --> 00:23:57.135
Next topic.

00:24:01.870 --> 00:24:05.260
I'm going to go back to
Alexandrov's theorem.

00:24:05.260 --> 00:24:08.620
Turns out there is a
smooth version of that.

00:24:08.620 --> 00:24:11.310
So now we're going
to segue a little bit

00:24:11.310 --> 00:24:14.215
into smooth foldings
and smooth unfoldings.

00:24:16.730 --> 00:24:20.140
So instead of thinking of
polyhedron objects-- polygons

00:24:20.140 --> 00:24:25.180
and convex polyhedra-- I want
to think about smooth bodies.

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:33.760
So, for example, suppose
I take a smooth convex

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:36.820
shape like an
ellipse or something

00:24:36.820 --> 00:24:39.950
and I picked two
perimeter antipodes

00:24:39.950 --> 00:24:49.191
and I do perimeter having
gluing where this is defines--

00:24:49.191 --> 00:24:51.190
as I walk along the
perimeter in both directions

00:24:51.190 --> 00:24:53.460
it-- I obviously
didn't do it perfectly,

00:24:53.460 --> 00:24:56.474
they should meet at
exactly the same time.

00:24:56.474 --> 00:24:57.390
This defines a gluing.

00:24:57.390 --> 00:24:59.100
For every point there
is a corresponding point

00:24:59.100 --> 00:24:59.900
it gets glued to.

00:24:59.900 --> 00:25:04.780
This is a way to make what is
locally like a convex surface

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:08.200
because at any point, at
most 360 degrees of material

00:25:08.200 --> 00:25:10.260
is glued there because
this thing was convex.

00:25:10.260 --> 00:25:13.020
And the same way as
for convex polygons,

00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:15.474
does this make a convex
something in three dimensions?

00:25:15.474 --> 00:25:17.390
It's not going to make
a polyhedron because it

00:25:17.390 --> 00:25:20.180
has this curve,
but indeed it does

00:25:20.180 --> 00:25:22.700
make a convex smooth surface.

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:40.660
So every convex metric
that's topologically a sphere

00:25:40.660 --> 00:25:46.225
is realized by a
unique convex surface.

00:25:54.210 --> 00:25:56.860
So Alexandrov's theorem was
identical to this statement

00:25:56.860 --> 00:25:59.430
except it also had
polyhedral up here,

00:25:59.430 --> 00:26:02.740
that there were finite number
of points of nonzero curvature.

00:26:02.740 --> 00:26:04.890
Now we have
infinitely many points

00:26:04.890 --> 00:26:07.550
of slightly positive
curvature because, again, this

00:26:07.550 --> 00:26:08.950
is supposed to sum to 4 pi.

00:26:08.950 --> 00:26:10.230
That's still true.

00:26:10.230 --> 00:26:13.067
But it's now an integral
instead of a sum.

00:26:13.067 --> 00:26:15.650
So each of these things sort of
has an infinitesimal curvature

00:26:15.650 --> 00:26:19.250
and if you integrate
them it adds up to 4 pi.

00:26:19.250 --> 00:26:22.190
You can check that.

00:26:22.190 --> 00:26:24.670
So this will make something.

00:26:24.670 --> 00:26:26.754
I encourage you to try
this out, again, with tape.

00:26:26.754 --> 00:26:28.545
You're going to
approximate it because tape

00:26:28.545 --> 00:26:29.830
is going to be polygonal.

00:26:29.830 --> 00:26:31.520
But it works.

00:26:31.520 --> 00:26:33.140
It will make something.

00:26:33.140 --> 00:26:36.620
I particularly-- I should
mention the idea of this proof

00:26:36.620 --> 00:26:39.110
is just to take limits
of regular Alexandrov.

00:26:39.110 --> 00:26:41.599
Take closer and closer
polyhedral approximations.

00:26:41.599 --> 00:26:43.640
In the polyhedral world
we can use that induction

00:26:43.640 --> 00:26:45.170
that we talked about.

00:26:45.170 --> 00:26:47.720
In the smooth case, you
can't, but the smooth case

00:26:47.720 --> 00:26:51.180
is the limit of the polyhedral
case so it works out.

00:26:51.180 --> 00:26:55.580
This is proved by a student
of Alexandrov Pogorelov

00:26:55.580 --> 00:26:59.860
in the '70s, whereas he
proved his theorem in the '40s

00:26:59.860 --> 00:27:01.558
or '50s.

00:27:01.558 --> 00:27:03.730
One really fun thing you
could do with this theorem

00:27:03.730 --> 00:27:07.550
is, instead of using
just one convex shape,

00:27:07.550 --> 00:27:12.389
you could use two convex shapes
and zip them to each other.

00:27:12.389 --> 00:27:13.555
And this is called a D-form.

00:27:13.555 --> 00:27:16.820
It was invented by an
artist, Tony Wills.

00:27:16.820 --> 00:27:18.572
So here I've taken
two-- in this case,

00:27:18.572 --> 00:27:20.030
two identical
convect shapes-- they

00:27:20.030 --> 00:27:23.240
don't have to be identical--
picked two points to glue them

00:27:23.240 --> 00:27:26.626
to each other and then you
just zip around the perimeter.

00:27:26.626 --> 00:27:29.250
And again, because you're always
gluing convex angles to convex

00:27:29.250 --> 00:27:31.060
angles-- the smooth
convex angles--

00:27:31.060 --> 00:27:34.840
but they're still less than
180, so you glue them together,

00:27:34.840 --> 00:27:36.760
it's less than 360.

00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:39.360
And in this case, it's-- we
could actually figure out

00:27:39.360 --> 00:27:42.230
and think about what 3D shape
you get so we could build that

00:27:42.230 --> 00:27:43.620
in Mathematica.

00:27:43.620 --> 00:27:47.060
But in general, you get
some weird convex shape.

00:27:47.060 --> 00:27:49.394
For a while there were
some examples of this

00:27:49.394 --> 00:27:51.310
but no one knew exactly
what they looked like.

00:27:51.310 --> 00:27:54.800
Then, I think it was a
project in this class

00:27:54.800 --> 00:27:57.180
or it came out of the problem
session in this class three

00:27:57.180 --> 00:27:59.900
years ago, Greg
Price and I proved

00:27:59.900 --> 00:28:02.930
that these things
are nice in the sense

00:28:02.930 --> 00:28:05.270
that the only place
you get creases

00:28:05.270 --> 00:28:08.820
is along the seam,
the pink stuff.

00:28:08.820 --> 00:28:11.310
Both for-- these
are called D-forms,

00:28:11.310 --> 00:28:13.960
these have another-- I
think these are pita-forms,

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:17.390
if I recall, where you take one
convex shape instead of two.

00:28:17.390 --> 00:28:20.060
Here you only get--
you can get the creases

00:28:20.060 --> 00:28:21.910
along the seam and
one extra crease,

00:28:21.910 --> 00:28:23.752
if I recall correctly here.

00:28:23.752 --> 00:28:25.460
And here you don't
get any extra creases.

00:28:25.460 --> 00:28:27.810
It's always smooth
except at the seam.

00:28:27.810 --> 00:28:31.020
And also, if you just take
the seam-- the pink part--

00:28:31.020 --> 00:28:35.030
and take the convex hull of that
thing, you get the same thing.

00:28:35.030 --> 00:28:37.050
So it doesn't go outside.

00:28:37.050 --> 00:28:40.240
It's really tightly
wrapped around wherever

00:28:40.240 --> 00:28:41.810
the seam happens to go.

00:28:41.810 --> 00:28:44.930
Remember, this thing is
unique by Pogorelov's theorem.

00:28:44.930 --> 00:28:48.060
So it's kind of nice to
know that structurally these

00:28:48.060 --> 00:28:49.530
are pretty nice and smooth.

00:28:49.530 --> 00:28:52.880
If your original shapes
are smooth convex bodies,

00:28:52.880 --> 00:28:55.340
you will get a
nice, smooth shape

00:28:55.340 --> 00:28:59.680
at the end that only has
creases at the seams.

00:28:59.680 --> 00:29:01.160
Cool.

00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:03.005
Again, please try to it at home.

00:29:03.005 --> 00:29:04.509
It's lots of fun.

00:29:04.509 --> 00:29:05.425
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:29:17.355 --> 00:29:18.230
PROFESSOR: Let's see.

00:29:18.230 --> 00:29:21.760
This point should glue to here.

00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:25.170
I mean, it's
perfectly symmetric.

00:29:25.170 --> 00:29:27.570
AUDIENCE: I'm looking
at the 3D form.

00:29:27.570 --> 00:29:28.690
PROFESSOR: The 3D form.

00:29:28.690 --> 00:29:33.200
So one of the two shapes
is here and the other one

00:29:33.200 --> 00:29:37.170
is here and goes around
the back to there.

00:29:37.170 --> 00:29:39.340
And it's, again, symmetric.

00:29:39.340 --> 00:29:42.630
This is a nice example because
we have those parallel lines.

00:29:42.630 --> 00:29:45.330
Usually you wouldn't have that.

00:29:45.330 --> 00:29:49.126
And they're harder to
draw, is the challenge.

00:29:49.126 --> 00:29:50.500
Here, obviously,
we're doing sort

00:29:50.500 --> 00:29:51.710
of a polygonal approximation.

00:29:51.710 --> 00:29:54.330
You see all the lines.

00:29:54.330 --> 00:29:55.980
All right.

00:29:55.980 --> 00:30:00.230
This is a smooth version of
folding-- a smooth version

00:30:00.230 --> 00:30:01.630
of Alexandrov's theorem.

00:30:01.630 --> 00:30:05.500
We can also think about
smooth versions of unfolding.

00:30:05.500 --> 00:30:10.520
So here there is
exactly one paper

00:30:10.520 --> 00:30:17.150
by Nadia Benbernou whose in
the front row and Heather--

00:30:17.150 --> 00:30:17.982
AUDIENCE: Patricia.

00:30:17.982 --> 00:30:21.880
PROFESSOR: Patricia
Khan and Joe O'Rourke.

00:30:21.880 --> 00:30:25.720
So this is a prismatoid.

00:30:25.720 --> 00:30:27.440
It's a little hard to
see the bottom face

00:30:27.440 --> 00:30:31.720
but there's a convex polygon on
the bottom, a parallel convex

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:32.890
polygon on the top.

00:30:32.890 --> 00:30:35.820
You take the convex hull--
sorry, they're not polygons.

00:30:35.820 --> 00:30:38.060
They're smooth convex bodies.

00:30:38.060 --> 00:30:40.640
So you've got one in the floor
plane, one in a parallel plane

00:30:40.640 --> 00:30:41.440
up top.

00:30:41.440 --> 00:30:44.300
You take the convex hull, you
get this nice smooth thing

00:30:44.300 --> 00:30:45.660
around the outside.

00:30:45.660 --> 00:30:48.570
Now, we have to generalize
our notion of unfolding

00:30:48.570 --> 00:30:50.690
because normally with
unfolding this would take

00:30:50.690 --> 00:30:53.410
an infinite number of cuts
to-- we have to cut everywhere

00:30:53.410 --> 00:30:54.160
there's curvature.

00:30:54.160 --> 00:30:55.993
Which means we're going
to have to cut along

00:30:55.993 --> 00:30:57.250
all those black lines.

00:30:57.250 --> 00:31:02.490
Which means we slice the thing
into very infinitesimal pieces.

00:31:02.490 --> 00:31:06.530
But if you think
of it as a limit

00:31:06.530 --> 00:31:11.630
of regular polyhedral things--
here I have a little example.

00:31:11.630 --> 00:31:16.370
Let's think about the limit in
a simpler example to start with.

00:31:16.370 --> 00:31:19.000
So imagine you want
to take a pyramid--

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:23.886
so the top poly-- the top
convex shape is just a point.

00:31:23.886 --> 00:31:25.645
I guess it looks like
a cone but down here

00:31:25.645 --> 00:31:32.180
it could be anything, could be
an ellipse or any convex shape.

00:31:32.180 --> 00:31:35.480
Well, we can think of this as
a polyhedral approximation.

00:31:35.480 --> 00:31:40.420
So, for example, we take
a hexagon on the bottom,

00:31:40.420 --> 00:31:42.590
we want to unfold that.

00:31:42.590 --> 00:31:45.160
And in particular, we
thought about these--

00:31:45.160 --> 00:31:49.520
these are the
pyramids-- and we--

00:31:49.520 --> 00:31:53.830
one of the unfoldings of
them is the volcano unfolding

00:31:53.830 --> 00:31:56.894
if you remember back to
the unfolding lecture.

00:31:56.894 --> 00:31:57.560
Looks like that.

00:31:57.560 --> 00:32:01.210
All these triangles just fold
out, get all those parts.

00:32:01.210 --> 00:32:03.660
That never overlaps,
it's sort of trivial.

00:32:03.660 --> 00:32:06.430
You take the limit of that.

00:32:06.430 --> 00:32:09.510
In the limit, the floor becomes
whatever the convex shape.

00:32:09.510 --> 00:32:14.240
Maybe-- let's think about the
simple case where it's a disk.

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:19.209
And in the limit you're getting
lots of really tiny triangles.

00:32:19.209 --> 00:32:21.500
You take that all the way to
limit, what you're getting

00:32:21.500 --> 00:32:26.950
is actually a concentric
circle around there.

00:32:26.950 --> 00:32:30.100
So really, these
become segments.

00:32:30.100 --> 00:32:33.970
Now, what's funny about
this limit is, normally--

00:32:33.970 --> 00:32:38.460
before you get to the end, you
see there's these big gaps.

00:32:38.460 --> 00:32:40.174
A lot of the area's missing.

00:32:40.174 --> 00:32:42.090
These things are getting
infinitesimally small

00:32:42.090 --> 00:32:44.570
and yet they have to
spread over this big range.

00:32:44.570 --> 00:32:46.650
So most of this area
is actually absent.

00:32:46.650 --> 00:32:49.066
When you take the limit you
can't really see that anymore.

00:32:49.066 --> 00:32:50.250
It just becomes filled in.

00:32:50.250 --> 00:32:55.860
And so in this unfolding,
the area of the green stuff,

00:32:55.860 --> 00:32:59.120
if you just took that area
measured on the floor,

00:32:59.120 --> 00:33:02.600
it's going to be larger
than the area in the pink.

00:33:02.600 --> 00:33:04.720
So this is not an area
preserving unfolding

00:33:04.720 --> 00:33:06.420
which makes it a little weird.

00:33:06.420 --> 00:33:07.920
But it's still well defined.

00:33:07.920 --> 00:33:10.311
I mean, you wouldn't
actually-- well,

00:33:10.311 --> 00:33:12.560
for example-- we're going
to get to this in a moment--

00:33:12.560 --> 00:33:15.850
if you actually took material
like this out of, say,

00:33:15.850 --> 00:33:18.570
tin foil, something
that can crinkle,

00:33:18.570 --> 00:33:22.290
then you should be able to
crinkle it into this shape.

00:33:22.290 --> 00:33:25.020
I'll talk about
how to prove that.

00:33:25.020 --> 00:33:27.020
That's actually most of
the rest of the lecture,

00:33:27.020 --> 00:33:29.090
is about that kind
of notion of folding.

00:33:29.090 --> 00:33:31.520
It's more like origami,
though, than unfolding

00:33:31.520 --> 00:33:35.020
because you're sort of
over covering stuff.

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:37.030
And here-- actually,
here the hard part

00:33:37.030 --> 00:33:40.110
is not so much to show
these ribs don't intersect,

00:33:40.110 --> 00:33:42.110
although they don't and
it's not totally obvious

00:33:42.110 --> 00:33:44.950
because here they're kind
of going towards each other.

00:33:44.950 --> 00:33:48.849
But they won't actually
intersect in the unfolding.

00:33:48.849 --> 00:33:51.390
One of the tricky parts is to
show that the top face actually

00:33:51.390 --> 00:33:53.150
can fit somewhere,
so you actually

00:33:53.150 --> 00:33:56.400
get an unfolding of this thing.

00:33:56.400 --> 00:34:01.220
And I forget, this is choosing
some kind of extreme rib

00:34:01.220 --> 00:34:02.665
and putting it out there.

00:34:02.665 --> 00:34:06.240
It's a nice line of
separation if I recall.

00:34:09.230 --> 00:34:14.000
This is funny because here we
have a limit of some process.

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:20.840
Now, for pyramids we know
the volcano unfolding works.

00:34:20.840 --> 00:34:23.850
For prismatoids,
regular prismatoids

00:34:23.850 --> 00:34:26.429
are when you take
some convex polygon

00:34:26.429 --> 00:34:30.250
and some other parallel convex
polygon, take the convex hull.

00:34:35.760 --> 00:34:38.620
We don't know whether
these have edge unfoldings.

00:34:38.620 --> 00:34:40.969
Still an open problem.

00:34:40.969 --> 00:34:44.440
And yet, for the
smooth case, we do.

00:34:44.440 --> 00:34:45.949
Kind of magical.

00:34:45.949 --> 00:34:47.219
I know why that's true.

00:34:47.219 --> 00:34:50.948
It's somehow the edge
constraint is harder.

00:34:50.948 --> 00:34:52.989
If you're not just worried
about edge unfoldings,

00:34:52.989 --> 00:34:55.260
we do know how to
unfold those obviously.

00:34:55.260 --> 00:34:58.310
You can do star unfolding,
source unfolding.

00:34:58.310 --> 00:35:00.946
Here, edge unfolding--
well, we have

00:35:00.946 --> 00:35:02.820
to cut along all those
infinitely many edges.

00:35:02.820 --> 00:35:04.610
That makes it easier,
much smoother.

00:35:08.132 --> 00:35:10.090
But it's funny when the
smooth case is actually

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:12.160
easier than the discrete case.

00:35:12.160 --> 00:35:12.660
All right.

00:35:15.250 --> 00:35:18.872
The next problem I want to
talk about is chocolate.

00:35:22.680 --> 00:35:26.100
I have here a bunch of
spherical chocolates.

00:35:26.100 --> 00:35:29.650
The most-- apparently the only
perfectly spherical chocolate,

00:35:29.650 --> 00:35:32.310
at least according
to the advertisement,

00:35:32.310 --> 00:35:34.640
is this thing called
the Mozart Kugel.

00:35:34.640 --> 00:35:38.230
Now, Mozart Kugel-- how many
people have eaten them before.

00:35:38.230 --> 00:35:39.671
Just a couple.

00:35:39.671 --> 00:35:40.170
Good stuff.

00:35:40.170 --> 00:35:43.530
It's, I guess, more
a European thing.

00:35:43.530 --> 00:35:44.790
It's from Austria.

00:35:44.790 --> 00:35:49.150
It's invented in early
1900s, I forget exactly when.

00:35:49.150 --> 00:35:51.677
It was a big thing at the
time because making chocolate

00:35:51.677 --> 00:35:53.010
perfectly spherical is not easy.

00:35:53.010 --> 00:35:55.230
It's like, how do
you hold it and not

00:35:55.230 --> 00:35:56.460
get little indentations?

00:35:56.460 --> 00:35:57.620
This thing is
perfectly spherical.

00:35:57.620 --> 00:35:58.411
Here I'll show you.

00:36:00.870 --> 00:36:06.040
But, really, the question I
wonder, because as an origamist

00:36:06.040 --> 00:36:08.270
you wonder, how do
you wrap this thing?

00:36:08.270 --> 00:36:10.065
Oh, I ripped it.

00:36:10.065 --> 00:36:11.595
I'll try to do this
more carefully.

00:36:15.820 --> 00:36:18.786
It's not how you usually
eat chocolate, is it?

00:36:18.786 --> 00:36:21.520
Open very carefully.

00:36:21.520 --> 00:36:22.020
It's OK.

00:36:22.020 --> 00:36:24.840
I have more in case I fail.

00:36:24.840 --> 00:36:25.475
More chocolate.

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.801
Not enough for you, I'm afraid.

00:36:31.801 --> 00:36:32.800
So ignore the chocolate.

00:36:36.410 --> 00:36:40.360
It's not the Droid
you're looking for.

00:36:40.360 --> 00:36:41.330
It's not the chocolate.

00:36:41.330 --> 00:36:42.830
So it's a rectangle.

00:36:42.830 --> 00:36:44.455
I didn't do a perfect job.

00:36:44.455 --> 00:36:46.070
There's a few
little tears there.

00:36:46.070 --> 00:36:48.320
But they fold-- Mirabell.

00:36:48.320 --> 00:36:52.737
Mirabell makes the most
Mozart Kugel in the world.

00:36:52.737 --> 00:36:54.320
Mozart Kugel is very
cool because it's

00:36:54.320 --> 00:36:56.900
built in-- built up
in concentric spheres.

00:36:56.900 --> 00:37:01.400
You have the marzipan layer,
then the milk chocolate layer,

00:37:01.400 --> 00:37:03.880
then the nougat layer, then
the dark chocolate layer,

00:37:03.880 --> 00:37:05.210
if I recall.

00:37:05.210 --> 00:37:08.530
Each brand has a
different recipe,

00:37:08.530 --> 00:37:11.324
but they're always
spherical on the outside.

00:37:11.324 --> 00:37:12.990
It's kind of like
glassblowing actually.

00:37:12.990 --> 00:37:15.430
It's kind of fun.

00:37:15.430 --> 00:37:19.340
And each company has a
slightly different way-- well,

00:37:19.340 --> 00:37:21.190
I've studied only
two main companies.

00:37:21.190 --> 00:37:25.320
Mirabell makes the most of them
but they are not the original.

00:37:25.320 --> 00:37:29.694
They are called the
echta which is--

00:37:29.694 --> 00:37:30.490
AUDIENCE: The real.

00:37:30.490 --> 00:37:32.360
PROFESSOR: The real.

00:37:32.360 --> 00:37:34.160
The authentic.

00:37:34.160 --> 00:37:37.880
But-- now, these
are hard to come by.

00:37:37.880 --> 00:37:41.470
These are brought to me by
my student, [INAUDIBLE],

00:37:41.470 --> 00:37:42.540
some of you know.

00:37:42.540 --> 00:37:44.519
Architecture.

00:37:44.519 --> 00:37:46.060
This is the-- oh,
it says in English.

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:46.930
It's kind of easy.

00:37:46.930 --> 00:37:50.000
The original Salzburger
Mozart Kugel.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:53.790
Mozart was-- lived
in Salzburg, I guess.

00:37:53.790 --> 00:37:55.510
And so this is named after him.

00:37:55.510 --> 00:37:56.460
Oh, 1884.

00:37:56.460 --> 00:37:57.580
Wow.

00:37:57.580 --> 00:37:59.310
So that's when they started.

00:37:59.310 --> 00:38:05.026
Now, these guys--
I think I've only

00:38:05.026 --> 00:38:06.400
had like one of
these in my life.

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:07.420
I'm really excited.

00:38:07.420 --> 00:38:09.962
The Mirabell's are
OK, but this stuff?

00:38:09.962 --> 00:38:10.462
Wow.

00:38:14.884 --> 00:38:16.300
Oh, it's so much
easier to unfold.

00:38:16.300 --> 00:38:18.810
I like-- this is, I
think, probably handmade.

00:38:18.810 --> 00:38:20.450
Much more handmade.

00:38:20.450 --> 00:38:23.980
In fact, you can kind of tell
