00:39:51.410 --> 00:39:55.400
this is not the origami you
grew up with in this class.

00:39:55.400 --> 00:39:58.430
Because you can't fold a
sphere out of a square paper.

00:39:58.430 --> 00:40:01.970
And yet, this was a square
folded into a sphere.

00:40:01.970 --> 00:40:06.650
Somehow that was done using
a finite amount of effort.

00:40:06.650 --> 00:40:09.510
Whereas if you use regular
paper to fold something

00:40:09.510 --> 00:40:11.650
that has positive
curvature everywhere,

00:40:11.650 --> 00:40:13.760
you need infinitely
many creases.

00:40:13.760 --> 00:40:15.500
And yet this is fairly
practical to do.

00:40:15.500 --> 00:40:16.980
This is hand wrapped.

00:40:16.980 --> 00:40:18.910
In theory, I could re-wrap this.

00:40:18.910 --> 00:40:20.570
I've never actually tried.

00:40:20.570 --> 00:40:21.760
But something like this.

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:23.215
It works pretty well.

00:40:23.215 --> 00:40:26.860
I even covered the tip.

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:28.320
How did I do that
in finite effort?

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:30.840
Well, of course it's
not a perfect sphere.

00:40:30.840 --> 00:40:33.490
But we need to model
this mathematically.

00:40:33.490 --> 00:40:35.625
It's annoying to
take approximations.

00:40:35.625 --> 00:40:37.500
I would like a model of
folding that actually

00:40:37.500 --> 00:40:40.470
does make it possible
to fold a sphere.

00:40:40.470 --> 00:40:44.490
So this is the idea of
contractive folding.

00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:54.210
We haven't been super rigorous
about defining origami,

00:40:54.210 --> 00:40:57.970
but I always say you
take a piece of paper,

00:40:57.970 --> 00:41:00.890
you can't stretch the paper,
you can't tear the paper,

00:41:00.890 --> 00:41:03.400
and you can't self-intersect.

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:06.980
We're going to relax the
you can't stretch the paper.

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:08.770
You still can't
stretch the paper,

00:41:08.770 --> 00:41:11.060
but now the paper can contract.

00:41:11.060 --> 00:41:13.110
So it can't get longer
but it can get shorter.

00:41:13.110 --> 00:41:15.640
It's like cables from
tensegrity theory.

00:41:15.640 --> 00:41:17.470
So you take any pair of points.

00:41:17.470 --> 00:41:20.300
There's some distance as
measured on the piece of paper.

00:41:20.300 --> 00:41:24.540
When you fold this thing
into your awesome sphere,

00:41:24.540 --> 00:41:26.750
you take the two points,
you measure the distance

00:41:26.750 --> 00:41:29.890
along the surface of
the piece of paper.

00:41:29.890 --> 00:41:31.910
Now, I'll-- normally
with origami,

00:41:31.910 --> 00:41:34.850
these two distances
should be equal.

00:41:34.850 --> 00:41:36.440
That's isometry.

00:41:36.440 --> 00:41:39.440
That's regular origami.

00:41:39.440 --> 00:41:45.190
But if I say that this one--
so write equal that way.

00:41:45.190 --> 00:41:51.490
If this one can be smaller,
then this is contractive.

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:55.920
And that is paper that can
shrink but not stretch.

00:41:55.920 --> 00:42:06.364
So pairwise distances
don't increase.

00:42:06.364 --> 00:42:07.530
So they could stay the same.

00:42:07.530 --> 00:42:09.710
We could still do
regular origami.

00:42:09.710 --> 00:42:12.070
But we can also contract.

00:42:12.070 --> 00:42:15.140
And then it is possible
to fold a sphere.

00:42:15.140 --> 00:42:17.690
Now, intuitively,
what's going on

00:42:17.690 --> 00:42:21.380
is, when you fold out of
tinfoil, you can crinkle.

00:42:21.380 --> 00:42:26.840
And that lets you not have
to worry about-- I mean,

00:42:26.840 --> 00:42:28.790
this is pretty good
approximation to a sphere

00:42:28.790 --> 00:42:31.040
especially when I have
a good base underneath

00:42:31.040 --> 00:42:35.090
to approximate against.

00:42:35.090 --> 00:42:38.250
I'm doing lots of little
tiny creases in order

00:42:38.250 --> 00:42:43.080
to approximate that contractive
mapping, contractive folding.

00:42:43.080 --> 00:42:47.350
So, conveniently,
there's a theorem

00:42:47.350 --> 00:42:49.590
that tells us this
is always possible.

00:42:49.590 --> 00:42:51.340
I'll tell you the theorem.

00:42:51.340 --> 00:42:55.350
This is another theorem
by Burago and Zalgallar

00:42:55.350 --> 00:42:59.560
who proved the other
theorem that if you

00:42:59.560 --> 00:43:04.380
have any polyhedral
metric you can turn it

00:43:04.380 --> 00:43:08.230
into some polyhedron,
not necessarily convex.

00:43:08.230 --> 00:43:11.610
So they solved that problem
plus they solved this problem.

00:43:11.610 --> 00:43:16.580
If you take a contractive-- they
only solved the smooth case.

00:43:16.580 --> 00:43:19.650
I imagine this works
for piecewise smooth.

00:43:19.650 --> 00:43:23.070
You take a contractive
C2 immersion--

00:43:23.070 --> 00:43:25.700
it's just some fancy
word for folding,

00:43:25.700 --> 00:43:29.060
it has some extra constraints
but let's not worry about it.

00:43:29.060 --> 00:43:31.490
So C2 means continuous up
to the second derivative.

00:43:31.490 --> 00:43:32.440
So nice and smooth.

00:43:32.440 --> 00:43:35.450
Spheres are valid, for example.

00:43:35.450 --> 00:43:42.714
Then any one of those
things has a C0--

00:43:42.714 --> 00:43:44.505
I'll just call it
polyhedral approximation.

00:43:48.570 --> 00:43:51.090
And this is approximation
in the Hausdorff sense

00:43:51.090 --> 00:43:54.300
meaning you want
to fold the sphere.

00:43:54.300 --> 00:43:57.200
If you just thicken that
sphere by some epsilon,

00:43:57.200 --> 00:44:00.570
then you can sort of stay within
that epsilon thickened sphere

00:44:00.570 --> 00:44:02.290
and do some kind of wiggling.

00:44:02.290 --> 00:44:04.120
You'll be polyhedral
and you'll only

00:44:04.120 --> 00:44:06.390
have finitely many creases.

00:44:06.390 --> 00:44:10.180
So there-- if you have a nice,
smooth contracted folded state,

00:44:10.180 --> 00:44:14.250
you could turn it into a regular
origami isometry folded state

00:44:14.250 --> 00:44:16.610
that's arbitrarily
close to the sphere.

00:44:16.610 --> 00:44:17.460
So for any epsilon.

00:44:21.090 --> 00:44:25.560
So that's a convenient
theorem from 1996.

00:44:25.560 --> 00:44:26.730
So that's the model.

00:44:26.730 --> 00:44:30.870
Now we can think about, how
do I optimally wrap a sphere?

00:44:30.870 --> 00:44:35.010
Now, there are
many possible goals

00:44:35.010 --> 00:44:38.450
you might want to optimize
in wrapping a sphere.

00:44:38.450 --> 00:44:40.630
Presumably, you want your
shape to tile the plane.

00:44:40.630 --> 00:44:42.505
So you can cut out a
whole bunch of these out

00:44:42.505 --> 00:44:44.780
of one sheet of tinfoil.

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:47.000
Obviously Mirabell
likes rectangles,

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:49.590
Furst likes squares.

00:44:49.590 --> 00:44:51.430
Are those the
right things to do?

00:44:51.430 --> 00:44:53.230
What about triangles?

00:44:53.230 --> 00:44:54.230
What about other shapes?

00:44:54.230 --> 00:44:56.104
These are the sorts of
questions we consider.

00:44:56.104 --> 00:44:58.220
We don't have a complete
answer to this question.

00:44:58.220 --> 00:45:01.642
But we have a lot of
fun-- fun things to do.

00:45:01.642 --> 00:45:03.100
What should I tell
you about first?

00:45:08.449 --> 00:45:09.240
I'm getting hungry.

00:45:11.070 --> 00:45:12.820
Maybe I'll have the
rest of that Mirabell.

00:45:12.820 --> 00:45:14.210
It's just sitting there.

00:45:14.210 --> 00:45:17.410
Half a Mozart Kugel,
can't have that.

00:45:17.410 --> 00:45:17.910
All right.

00:45:17.910 --> 00:45:19.165
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:19.165 --> 00:45:19.790
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:45:19.790 --> 00:45:21.105
Question?

00:45:21.105 --> 00:45:22.230
AUDIENCE: I was wondering--

00:45:22.230 --> 00:45:24.790
PROFESSOR: You can have any.

00:45:24.790 --> 00:45:26.622
AUDIENCE: Because of
the fact that you've

00:45:26.622 --> 00:45:29.330
got this contracting
that occurs,

00:45:29.330 --> 00:45:32.645
I was wondering-- it's obvious
that because of contracting

00:45:32.645 --> 00:45:39.920
you need more than 4 pi
r surface area of paper

00:45:39.920 --> 00:45:44.590
to wrap a sphere--
a one unit sphere.

00:45:44.590 --> 00:45:47.790
I'm wondering, do you
know exactly how much

00:45:47.790 --> 00:45:50.041
paper do you require due to
the fact that [INAUDIBLE]?

00:45:50.041 --> 00:45:51.081
PROFESSOR: Good question.

00:45:51.081 --> 00:45:52.360
How much paper do you require?

00:45:52.360 --> 00:45:53.950
Area is not being
preserved here.

00:45:53.950 --> 00:45:57.170
Just like the continuous
unfolding stuff,

00:45:57.170 --> 00:45:58.790
you don't preserve area.

00:45:58.790 --> 00:46:00.040
This is really the same thing.

00:46:00.040 --> 00:46:02.075
I think you can prove
this is a contractive map.

00:46:02.075 --> 00:46:03.700
So if you had this
as a piece of paper,

00:46:03.700 --> 00:46:08.510
you really could fold
that smooth pyramid.

00:46:11.570 --> 00:46:14.790
But you lose material when
you do a contractive mapping.

00:46:14.790 --> 00:46:17.880
And in the inverse, when you're
unfolding, you gain material.

00:46:17.880 --> 00:46:21.395
How much material
do I have to gain?

00:46:21.395 --> 00:46:22.020
Think about it.

00:46:22.020 --> 00:46:23.830
You should be able to
answer that question.

00:46:23.830 --> 00:46:28.190
I'm going to tell you about some
stuff while you think about it.

00:46:28.190 --> 00:46:31.140
That was the original
question we started with.

00:46:31.140 --> 00:46:35.330
What's the minimum area
wrapping of a unit sphere?

00:46:35.330 --> 00:46:38.847
The surface area of a
sphere is 4 pi, FYI.

00:46:38.847 --> 00:46:39.930
How much more do you need?

00:46:42.570 --> 00:46:43.230
All right.

00:46:43.230 --> 00:46:46.960
To describe these unfoldings,
I guess they are, or wrappings,

00:46:46.960 --> 00:46:49.434
whichever way you're
thinking about going,

00:46:49.434 --> 00:46:51.100
it's useful to have
some structure, kind

00:46:51.100 --> 00:46:52.590
of a backbone to the unfolding.

00:46:52.590 --> 00:46:55.400
So we came up with this
idea of stretched path.

00:46:55.400 --> 00:46:57.770
And you can show that any
kind of optimal wrapping

00:46:57.770 --> 00:47:00.260
will have at least
one stretch path.

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:02.820
And our idea is
actually-- let me tell you

00:47:02.820 --> 00:47:04.670
what a stretch path is.

00:47:04.670 --> 00:47:10.830
This is a, let's say, a
path between two vertices

00:47:10.830 --> 00:47:12.990
whose length does not decrease.

00:47:12.990 --> 00:47:19.850
So it actually is
preserved in the folding.

00:47:29.190 --> 00:47:32.150
So I have my sphere,
I have two points,

00:47:32.150 --> 00:47:33.960
take the shortest
path between them.

00:47:33.960 --> 00:47:35.660
That shortest path
is exactly what

00:47:35.660 --> 00:47:38.327
it is in the unfolding,
exactly the same length.

00:47:38.327 --> 00:47:39.910
So that's what we
call a stretch path.

00:47:39.910 --> 00:47:41.610
There's no crinkling
along that path.

00:47:41.610 --> 00:47:44.150
There maybe crinkling on
either side of the path,

00:47:44.150 --> 00:47:46.550
but not on it.

00:47:46.550 --> 00:47:50.500
Our idea is-- OK, that gives
you some kind of structure.

00:47:50.500 --> 00:47:52.740
Our idea is to completely
cover the surface

00:47:52.740 --> 00:47:55.777
of the sphere with
stretched paths.

00:47:55.777 --> 00:47:57.360
There's a lot of
ways you can do that.

00:47:57.360 --> 00:48:00.270
Some of them will be valid,
some of them won't be.

00:48:00.270 --> 00:48:03.469
The simplest one is
the source unfolding.

00:48:03.469 --> 00:48:05.510
Or I guess you could call
it the source wrapping.

00:48:08.720 --> 00:48:12.090
Wrapping somehow means
contractive I guess.

00:48:12.090 --> 00:48:15.550
Which is, you take your
sphere, take some point x,

00:48:15.550 --> 00:48:17.992
you take all the
shortest paths around x--

00:48:17.992 --> 00:48:19.200
it's a little tricky to draw.

00:48:22.697 --> 00:48:24.780
In other words, the Voronoi
diagram at that point.

00:48:24.780 --> 00:48:27.200
Just like we did with
source unfolding.

00:48:27.200 --> 00:48:31.180
And you call all of these edges,
all those straight lines--

00:48:31.180 --> 00:48:36.020
geodesics, whatever-- they go to
this opposite south pole here.

00:48:36.020 --> 00:48:40.130
All of those lines you
call stretch paths.

00:48:40.130 --> 00:48:42.210
That determines an unfolding.

00:48:42.210 --> 00:48:44.720
And it happens to
be contractive.

00:48:44.720 --> 00:48:48.070
The unfolding will be a
big disk because you'll

00:48:48.070 --> 00:48:51.750
have the center-- call this x.

00:48:51.750 --> 00:48:54.500
This is 3D, this is 2D,
in case it wasn't clear.

00:48:54.500 --> 00:48:56.250
They both look the same.

00:48:56.250 --> 00:48:57.850
But now all those
paths are straight.

00:49:00.960 --> 00:49:03.260
And it's clear what the
lengths of these paths are.

00:49:03.260 --> 00:49:08.927
Each one of them is
half the circumference.

00:49:08.927 --> 00:49:09.510
Circumference?

00:49:09.510 --> 00:49:10.551
Is that what you call it?

00:49:10.551 --> 00:49:13.050
Half of an equator
of the sphere.

00:49:13.050 --> 00:49:16.350
Which for a unit sphere is pi.

00:49:16.350 --> 00:49:24.020
So this is radius pi, which
means the area of this thing

00:49:24.020 --> 00:49:25.750
is pi r squared.

00:49:25.750 --> 00:49:28.380
Sorry, the area is pi cubed.

00:49:31.110 --> 00:49:32.610
Interesting.

00:49:32.610 --> 00:49:38.910
But pi cubed, you can
compute, is more than 4pi.

00:49:38.910 --> 00:49:43.580
Pi squared is
almost-- is over nine.

00:49:43.580 --> 00:49:45.480
It's over nine times pi.

00:49:45.480 --> 00:49:47.130
We want four times pi.

00:49:47.130 --> 00:49:49.340
This is an example of
not preserving area.

00:49:49.340 --> 00:49:51.680
What's happening is
there's lots of crinkling

00:49:51.680 --> 00:49:52.604
between these lines.

00:49:52.604 --> 00:49:54.520
Now, there are infinitely
many of these lines.

00:49:54.520 --> 00:49:58.340
Every point is covered by
one of these stretched paths.

00:49:58.340 --> 00:50:00.460
But again, when I
unfold them, if I

00:50:00.460 --> 00:50:03.760
did a limiting approximation,
there'd be lots of holes here.

00:50:03.760 --> 00:50:05.326
But in the limit
there are no holes

00:50:05.326 --> 00:50:06.700
and that's where
I waste material

00:50:06.700 --> 00:50:08.510
and that's where
I get contraction.

00:50:08.510 --> 00:50:09.495
Make sense?

00:50:09.495 --> 00:50:13.022
I actually brought a
sphere, a couple spheres.

00:50:13.022 --> 00:50:15.230
I brought some chocolate
spheres, but slightly bigger

00:50:15.230 --> 00:50:18.120
sphere so we can
think about this.

00:50:18.120 --> 00:50:22.840
In this case, we're making
stretch paths all around

00:50:22.840 --> 00:50:25.145
from the north pole
down to the south pole

00:50:25.145 --> 00:50:27.320
and kind of cutting
at the south pole.

00:50:27.320 --> 00:50:29.812
And that's it.

00:50:29.812 --> 00:50:30.788
All right.

00:50:34.700 --> 00:50:39.680
Has anyone solved the problem
of what the minimum area

00:50:39.680 --> 00:50:42.480
wrapping of the sphere is?

00:50:42.480 --> 00:50:42.980
Yeah?

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:43.720
You solved it?

00:50:43.720 --> 00:50:44.570
Janine.

00:50:44.570 --> 00:50:45.360
Or an idea.

00:50:45.360 --> 00:50:47.320
AUDIENCE: I think
it's 4pi plus epsilon.

00:50:47.320 --> 00:50:49.219
PROFESSOR: 4pi plus
epsilon is correct.

00:50:49.219 --> 00:50:50.260
How do you want to do it?

00:50:53.680 --> 00:50:54.380
Exactly.

00:50:54.380 --> 00:50:56.810
AUDIENCE: An apple
core-- or peeling.

00:50:56.810 --> 00:50:59.480
PROFESSOR: Apple peeling, yes.

00:50:59.480 --> 00:51:01.860
Or I prefer to think
of it as lecturer--

00:51:01.860 --> 00:51:04.670
I don't know which one--
the one about strip folding.

00:51:04.670 --> 00:51:06.630
AUDIENCE: Oh, yeah.

00:51:06.630 --> 00:51:07.470
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:51:07.470 --> 00:51:09.260
Exactly.

00:51:09.260 --> 00:51:11.700
So we had this result
about strip folding

00:51:11.700 --> 00:51:17.364
if you remember way back in
the folding anything lecture.

00:51:17.364 --> 00:51:19.030
We talked about this
and then orgamizer.

00:51:19.030 --> 00:51:20.450
This was the inefficient method.

00:51:20.450 --> 00:51:24.580
But if you started with a
very long rectangle of paper,

00:51:24.580 --> 00:51:28.490
we could show that the
area of that piece of paper

00:51:28.490 --> 00:51:30.540
is arbitrary-- could
be made arbitrarily

00:51:30.540 --> 00:51:32.805
close to the area
of your polyhedron.

00:51:36.380 --> 00:51:38.036
So that area plus some epsilon.

00:51:38.036 --> 00:51:39.410
And you can make
epsilon as small

00:51:39.410 --> 00:51:43.650
as you wanted just by
making this polygon longer.

00:51:43.650 --> 00:51:46.780
If you take a polyhedral
approximation of a sphere

00:51:46.780 --> 00:51:50.180
and apply this theorem, you'll
get very close to the surface

00:51:50.180 --> 00:51:52.770
area of that approximation which
is very close to the surface

00:51:52.770 --> 00:51:54.960
area of the sphere,
which is 4pi.

00:51:58.720 --> 00:52:01.170
And then, if you take
an outer approximation,

00:52:01.170 --> 00:52:04.430
then you can just sort of
crinkle all those vertices down

00:52:04.430 --> 00:52:05.920
against the sphere.

00:52:05.920 --> 00:52:08.460
And you'll do-- it's
maybe not totally obvious,

00:52:08.460 --> 00:52:09.887
but it's not that hard.

00:52:09.887 --> 00:52:12.470
You get a contractive map that
actually wraps the sphere using

00:52:12.470 --> 00:52:16.465
not much more surface
area than what you had.

00:52:16.465 --> 00:52:18.090
The same as what you
had, which was not

00:52:18.090 --> 00:52:19.280
much more than the sphere.

00:52:19.280 --> 00:52:21.020
So you can get 4pi plus epsilon.

00:52:21.020 --> 00:52:23.860
So it turns out, minimizing
the area of your wrapping

00:52:23.860 --> 00:52:26.272
is not that interesting
a question by itself

00:52:26.272 --> 00:52:28.230
because there's kind of
this cheating solution.

00:52:28.230 --> 00:52:30.146
Obviously, you don't
want to manufacture that.

00:52:30.146 --> 00:52:31.380
I don't think.

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:35.660
Maybe she built a robot, did
the inverse orange peeling,

00:52:35.660 --> 00:52:38.229
it would be pretty cool.

00:52:38.229 --> 00:52:40.520
But if you're trying to sell
this idea to confectioners

00:52:40.520 --> 00:52:43.499
around the world, I
wouldn't recommend

00:52:43.499 --> 00:52:44.540
attempting strip folding.

00:52:44.540 --> 00:52:46.030
So we would like
something that's

00:52:46.030 --> 00:52:51.410
reasonably nice but-- yeah.

00:52:51.410 --> 00:52:52.250
OK.

00:52:52.250 --> 00:52:54.695
AUDIENCE: So if
you're trying sell

00:52:54.695 --> 00:53:00.563
wrapper companies [INAUDIBLE]
square or rectangular amounts

00:53:00.563 --> 00:53:03.008
would these be 4pi squared?

00:53:03.008 --> 00:53:05.453
Because you're basically
producing something

00:53:05.453 --> 00:53:09.320
that maybe would expand
the circumference and--

00:53:09.320 --> 00:53:11.320
PROFESSOR: Well, OK, an
interesting question is,

00:53:11.320 --> 00:53:14.524
what is the surface
area of these wrappings?

00:53:14.524 --> 00:53:16.440
These actually have
pretty special properties,

00:53:16.440 --> 00:53:18.970
the rectangle and
the-- I'm getting

00:53:18.970 --> 00:53:20.440
hungry-- and the square.

00:53:23.940 --> 00:53:28.236
Have you thought about which
of these has more surface area?

00:53:28.236 --> 00:53:30.030
The rectangle has more?

00:53:30.030 --> 00:53:32.110
Who thinks the
rectangle has more?

00:53:32.110 --> 00:53:34.474
Who thinks the square has more?

00:53:34.474 --> 00:53:35.640
Who thinks they're the same?

00:53:39.140 --> 00:53:41.640
Seed you with that idea.

00:53:41.640 --> 00:53:43.220
Well, they're actually the same.

00:53:43.220 --> 00:53:46.199
I'll explain why
in a little bit.

00:53:46.199 --> 00:53:46.990
It's crazy, I know.

00:53:51.580 --> 00:53:54.845
I prefer the square because
it has less perimeter.

00:54:00.010 --> 00:54:01.920
There are obviously many
things you might not

00:54:01.920 --> 00:54:03.750
like about this strip folding.

00:54:03.750 --> 00:54:06.740
It has high aspect
ratio, but in particular,

00:54:06.740 --> 00:54:08.620
one way to characterize
why this is nasty,

00:54:08.620 --> 00:54:10.630
it says high perimeter.

00:54:10.630 --> 00:54:14.915
Perimeter is annoying
because-- for a few reasons.

00:54:14.915 --> 00:54:16.706
Intuitively, if you
started with the sphere

00:54:16.706 --> 00:54:18.890
and you wanted to
cut it open, then you

00:54:18.890 --> 00:54:21.070
need a lot of cutting
because the perimeter is

00:54:21.070 --> 00:54:22.860
the amount that you cut.

00:54:22.860 --> 00:54:25.150
Or it's twice that.

00:54:25.150 --> 00:54:29.382
So conversely, when you're
trying to wrap a surface,

00:54:29.382 --> 00:54:30.840
if you have high
perimeter, there's

00:54:30.840 --> 00:54:34.200
a lot to worry about, lots of
things that have to match up.

00:54:34.200 --> 00:54:36.740
So you've got to be very
careful in your crinkling.

00:54:36.740 --> 00:54:38.698
Whereas I really didn't
have to be very careful

00:54:38.698 --> 00:54:42.140
wrapping with the square
because it has low perimeter.

00:54:42.140 --> 00:54:44.310
Another sense in which
perimeter is annoying

00:54:44.310 --> 00:54:46.870
is you're going to
have some error.

00:54:46.870 --> 00:54:51.400
So in fact, you can't just
perfectly wrap a sphere.

00:54:51.400 --> 00:54:53.740
Like, if I took a disk
of exactly this size,

00:54:53.740 --> 00:54:56.100
I probably couldn't
wrap a sphere with it

00:54:56.100 --> 00:54:58.762
because I'm going to
lose just some epsilon

00:54:58.762 --> 00:55:00.220
and then there'll
be a little point

00:55:00.220 --> 00:55:03.720
around the south
pole that's missing.

00:55:03.720 --> 00:55:06.030
If you're really going to
build confectionery-- build

00:55:06.030 --> 00:55:08.890
confectionery-- if you're really
going to wrap confectionery,

00:55:08.890 --> 00:55:10.860
you probably make this
a little bit bigger.

00:55:10.860 --> 00:55:14.510
How much area do
you lose when you

00:55:14.510 --> 00:55:16.010
make your thing a
little bit bigger?

00:55:16.010 --> 00:55:18.637
Well, it's roughly the
perimeter times epsilon.

00:55:18.637 --> 00:55:21.220
It's a little bit different from
that, but basically perimeter

00:55:21.220 --> 00:55:22.080
times epsilon.

00:55:22.080 --> 00:55:24.050
So if you minimize
perimeter, then

00:55:24.050 --> 00:55:27.944
your area wastage from
double coverage will go down.

00:55:27.944 --> 00:55:29.360
So really what I
want is something

00:55:29.360 --> 00:55:33.140
that's low area
and low perimeter.

00:55:33.140 --> 00:55:35.090
That's our new goal.

00:55:35.090 --> 00:55:37.820
And that's why I like
Furst better than Mirabell,

00:55:37.820 --> 00:55:39.510
not just because
they taste better.

00:55:39.510 --> 00:55:42.222
I really should verify
that they taste better.

00:55:42.222 --> 00:55:45.010
Oh, yeah.

00:55:45.010 --> 00:55:47.520
Now, they're very
different insides.

00:55:47.520 --> 00:55:50.580
Oh, but it's so good.

00:55:50.580 --> 00:55:52.230
Oh, much better chocolate.

00:55:52.230 --> 00:55:52.740
All right.

00:56:00.548 --> 00:56:04.160
Maybe I should have a
lottery for eating the rest.

00:56:07.890 --> 00:56:08.570
Petal wrapping.

00:56:12.790 --> 00:56:16.010
This is going to be
another way to put stretch

00:56:16.010 --> 00:56:18.450
paths on the sphere and
get an unfolding-- get

00:56:18.450 --> 00:56:21.410
a contractive
wrapping from that.

00:56:21.410 --> 00:56:23.391
Which actually
corresponds to this toy.

00:56:23.391 --> 00:56:25.140
I don't know if you
ever played with this.

00:56:25.140 --> 00:56:26.460
The Frisbee that's also a ball.

00:56:29.120 --> 00:56:30.940
These-- you see those cuts?

00:56:33.839 --> 00:56:35.630
Those are the shortest
paths from the north

00:56:35.630 --> 00:56:38.200
pole to the south pole.

00:56:38.200 --> 00:56:41.030
But we're not--
before we were sort

00:56:41.030 --> 00:56:44.650
of using-- kind of slicing
along but also preserving--

00:56:44.650 --> 00:56:47.780
that's kind of confusing--
all of them, infinitely many.

00:56:47.780 --> 00:56:49.280
Now I want to do
with finitely many.

00:56:49.280 --> 00:56:51.240
Here I only have six.

00:56:51.240 --> 00:56:52.800
Six?

00:56:52.800 --> 00:56:53.450
Yes, six.

00:56:56.772 --> 00:56:57.730
Doesn't have to be six.

00:56:57.730 --> 00:57:00.260
Could be any number k.

00:57:00.260 --> 00:57:07.070
So I'm going to look at k
stretch paths from north pole

00:57:07.070 --> 00:57:07.850
to south pole.

00:57:07.850 --> 00:57:11.190
So I have my sphere,
here is my north pole.

00:57:11.190 --> 00:57:15.200
I do some constant number.

00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:17.370
Here I've done five.

00:57:17.370 --> 00:57:21.147
This is equally spaced
angular around the north pole,

00:57:21.147 --> 00:57:22.980
they all go to the south
pole on the bottom.

00:57:26.270 --> 00:57:27.924
Something like that.

00:57:27.924 --> 00:57:29.340
It's going to start
getting messy.

00:57:32.160 --> 00:57:33.790
These are going to
be stretch paths.

00:57:33.790 --> 00:57:38.910
I have to fill these orange
slices in between them.

00:57:38.910 --> 00:57:41.630
How should I fill them?

00:57:41.630 --> 00:57:44.457
Here's an idea.

00:57:44.457 --> 00:57:46.040
It's kind of like
the Voronoi diagram.

00:57:46.040 --> 00:57:51.485
Voronoi diagram is you grow from
many objects simultaneously.

00:57:51.485 --> 00:57:54.550
With this sphere wrapping
we grew from a single point

00:57:54.550 --> 00:57:57.130
in all directions.

00:57:57.130 --> 00:57:57.800
That was it.

00:57:57.800 --> 00:57:59.380
Now, I've drawn these paths.

00:57:59.380 --> 00:58:04.120
What if I grew from all of these
finite stretch paths at once?

00:58:04.120 --> 00:58:07.299
What I would get, these
would at some point converge.

00:58:07.299 --> 00:58:09.340
They would converge at
the angular bisector here.

00:58:13.760 --> 00:58:15.560
Along the way,
what's happening is

00:58:15.560 --> 00:58:20.330
each of these points is kind of
tracing along a straight line,

00:58:20.330 --> 00:58:22.910
so to speak, a
great circular arc

00:58:22.910 --> 00:58:25.640
until it reaches that point.

00:58:25.640 --> 00:58:28.670
I'm going to make
these stretched paths,

00:58:28.670 --> 00:58:31.794
and these are also stretched
pads, and basically cutting

00:58:31.794 --> 00:58:32.710
along the dotted line.

00:58:36.310 --> 00:58:36.810
OK.

00:58:36.810 --> 00:58:38.800
I won't draw all of them.

00:58:38.800 --> 00:58:39.860
But you get the idea.

00:58:39.860 --> 00:58:43.015
When you unfold this thing, you
have these kind of wish bones.

00:58:52.540 --> 00:58:55.430
These guys meet sort
of perpendicularly.

00:58:55.430 --> 00:58:57.702
So when you unfold you
preserve those angles.

00:58:57.702 --> 00:58:59.160
Remember these are
stretched paths.

00:58:59.160 --> 00:59:01.430
These lengths are preserved.

00:59:01.430 --> 00:59:04.780
The stuff in between,
it's really a curved thing

00:59:04.780 --> 00:59:07.380
and it gets slightly
larger in this thing.

00:59:07.380 --> 00:59:10.400
We call this thing a petal.

00:59:10.400 --> 00:59:12.590
But this is an
unfolding of this sort

00:59:12.590 --> 00:59:14.580
of one fifth of the sphere.

00:59:14.580 --> 00:59:18.660
This is the center line and
these are the two sides.

00:59:18.660 --> 00:59:23.540
So that's the idea
of petal wrapping.

00:59:23.540 --> 00:59:26.950
Now, there's different ways
to join these petals together.

00:59:26.950 --> 00:59:31.020
One idea is join them
all at the north pole.

00:59:31.020 --> 00:59:33.390
So then what you get--
it's a little hard

00:59:33.390 --> 00:59:36.020
to imagine that these things
don't intersect each other,

00:59:36.020 --> 00:59:38.120
especially when I've
drawn them so fat.

00:59:38.120 --> 00:59:40.245
For five, it's going to
look something like this.

00:59:43.159 --> 00:59:44.200
I'm drawing it perfectly.

00:59:46.659 --> 00:59:48.450
They won't actually
intersect in the center

00:59:48.450 --> 00:59:50.533
because the total amount
of material at the center

00:59:50.533 --> 00:59:52.660
is only 360 degrees.

00:59:52.660 --> 00:59:56.250
And this will actually have--
the tangents will actually

00:59:56.250 --> 00:59:57.090
match up here.

00:59:57.090 --> 00:59:59.380
So they will perfectly
mean in the center

00:59:59.380 --> 01:00:01.810
without self-intersection.

01:00:01.810 --> 01:00:03.610
So it's only sort of
a vertex unfolding.

01:00:03.610 --> 01:00:05.180
Because they're only
connected at the single point.

01:00:05.180 --> 01:00:06.710
But that's maybe necessary.

01:00:06.710 --> 01:00:07.702
I don't know.

01:00:07.702 --> 01:00:09.410
And again, these are
the stretched paths.

01:00:12.540 --> 01:00:15.450
It's a neat way to
think about unfolding.

01:00:15.450 --> 01:00:20.160
You can draw these--
ignore the yellow for now.

01:00:20.160 --> 01:00:22.734
That's if you might want
to actually cut these out.

01:00:22.734 --> 01:00:24.650
So we have the three
petal unfolding, the four

01:00:24.650 --> 01:00:26.770
petal unfolding, five
petal unfolding, six petal,

01:00:26.770 --> 01:00:28.920
you can go arbitrarily high.

01:00:28.920 --> 01:00:32.610
In the limit, the
area of the blue stuff

01:00:32.610 --> 01:00:35.320
will converge to 4pi.

01:00:35.320 --> 01:00:37.279
This is another way to
get arbitrarily close.

01:00:37.279 --> 01:00:38.820
Because the smaller
these things are,

01:00:38.820 --> 01:00:39.945
the less you're distorting.

01:00:43.680 --> 01:00:45.530
So this is two
families of wrappings.

01:00:45.530 --> 01:00:48.100
We call these-- the blue
stuff is the petal unfolding,

01:00:48.100 --> 01:00:52.050
the yellow is the convex
hull of the petal unfoldings.

01:00:52.050 --> 01:00:53.760
Not quite, actually.

01:00:53.760 --> 01:01:00.090
So in the case of k equals 3,
we could think about a convex

01:01:00.090 --> 01:01:02.110
hull, but what I've drawn
here is the smallest

01:01:02.110 --> 01:01:04.880
enclosing equilateral triangle.

01:01:04.880 --> 01:01:07.060
Now this is the first
class of unfoldings

01:01:07.060 --> 01:01:10.690
we came up with after
the obvious sphere--

01:01:10.690 --> 01:01:16.860
or circular one which
had pi cubed over 9pi.

01:01:16.860 --> 01:01:21.090
One thing we wondered
is that triangle,

01:01:21.090 --> 01:01:26.550
is it better than the
Mozart Kugel wrappings?

01:01:26.550 --> 01:01:28.636
Or is it worse?

01:01:28.636 --> 01:01:30.010
One way or the
other, presumably.

01:01:30.010 --> 01:01:31.290
Or maybe it's the same again.

01:01:31.290 --> 01:01:33.280
Who knows.

01:01:33.280 --> 01:01:33.780
Let's see.

01:01:36.601 --> 01:01:37.100
Yeah.

01:01:37.100 --> 01:01:40.624
Let me tell you, at this point--
so I need more techniques

01:01:40.624 --> 01:01:42.040
to cover both of
those unfoldings,

01:01:42.040 --> 01:01:46.980
but that square is
the first wrapping.

01:01:46.980 --> 01:01:48.274
This one.

01:01:48.274 --> 01:01:50.440
I'll have to unfold another
one just so you can see.

01:01:53.702 --> 01:01:54.640
All right.

01:01:54.640 --> 01:01:57.510
So you see-- I mean,
I did a few times

01:01:57.510 --> 01:01:59.000
so maybe you already know.

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:01.890
Here I have four corners,
four right angles.

01:02:01.890 --> 01:02:04.110
They meet at the top.

01:02:04.110 --> 01:02:07.320
So that is-- that's
where the four

01:02:07.320 --> 01:02:08.820
corners of the
square which are also

01:02:08.820 --> 01:02:11.980
the four corners of the
petal come together.

01:02:11.980 --> 01:02:16.000
And then it's just
everything-- these lines

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:17.480
are stretched paths.

01:02:17.480 --> 01:02:20.330
There's no distortion around
them, they just kind of unfold.

01:02:20.330 --> 01:02:26.010
The stuff in the middle is--
it's like undressing here.

01:02:26.010 --> 01:02:27.890
It's so tantalizing.

01:02:27.890 --> 01:02:31.120
The stuff in the middle
is getting contracted.

01:02:31.120 --> 01:02:33.860
So if-- I don't know if you
could see, maybe in the video

01:02:33.860 --> 01:02:35.040
you'll be able to see.

01:02:35.040 --> 01:02:36.900
Look closely at here.

01:02:36.900 --> 01:02:40.950
Along this path there
isn't so much crinkling.

01:02:40.950 --> 01:02:42.670
In between there's a
lot more crinkling.

01:02:42.670 --> 01:02:43.990
It's like here there's
a lot of crinkling.

01:02:43.990 --> 01:02:45.460
When I unfold it,
a lot more stuff

01:02:45.460 --> 01:02:49.121
happens in between
the four top paths.

01:02:49.121 --> 01:02:49.620
OK?

01:02:49.620 --> 01:02:53.160
Now, they wanted to
cut very simple shapes.

01:02:53.160 --> 01:02:55.320
In particular, shapes
that tiled the plane.

01:02:55.320 --> 01:02:59.420
So they ended up using squares
instead of the sort of optimal

01:02:59.420 --> 01:03:02.555
with that stretched paths
which are those four petals.

01:03:05.122 --> 01:03:07.080
So they used the yellow,
whereas you could just

01:03:07.080 --> 01:03:07.770
get away with the blue.

01:03:07.770 --> 01:03:09.895
Of course, you want to add
a little bit of material

01:03:09.895 --> 01:03:12.680
in the center so it
doesn't fall apart.

01:03:12.680 --> 01:03:15.040
And you need to thicken
the edges a little bit.

01:03:15.040 --> 01:03:19.740
So they care about that little
yellow minus blue savings?

01:03:19.740 --> 01:03:21.056
I'm not sure.

01:03:21.056 --> 01:03:24.330
But what about the triangle?

01:03:24.330 --> 01:03:26.980
We spend a lot of time
computing these shapes.

01:03:26.980 --> 01:03:28.800
It's some weird trigonometry.

01:03:28.800 --> 01:03:30.360
It's in the notes.

01:03:30.360 --> 01:03:33.540
Arc sine of sine over square
root of 1 over sine squared

01:03:33.540 --> 01:03:36.250
minus cos squared of
various parameters

01:03:36.250 --> 01:03:39.435
is the description of
one of these curves.

01:03:39.435 --> 01:03:41.060
So we did all this
computation and then

01:03:41.060 --> 01:03:44.680
we integrated it to compute
what these areas were and then--

01:03:44.680 --> 01:03:47.690
or figure out exactly what these
shapes were, take the tangents,

01:03:47.690 --> 01:03:50.780
say, well, is the smallest
enclosing triangle better

01:03:50.780 --> 01:03:52.940
or worse than the square?

01:03:52.940 --> 01:03:58.545
It turns out it's
better by 0.1%.

01:04:02.620 --> 01:04:05.780
Now, I think-- millions
of Mozart Kugel

01:04:05.780 --> 01:04:07.430
are made every year.

01:04:07.430 --> 01:04:13.200
0.1% could equate
to huge savings.

01:04:13.200 --> 01:04:14.790
Dollars.

01:04:14.790 --> 01:04:16.710
But just think of
the material wastage

01:04:16.710 --> 01:04:20.830
that Furst is committing
by using the square.

01:04:20.830 --> 01:04:23.090
If they used the
triangle instead,

01:04:23.090 --> 01:04:25.830
I mean, this could
solve global warming.

01:04:25.830 --> 01:04:27.565
This could solve
chocolate melting.

01:04:31.580 --> 01:04:34.230
We actually talk about global
warming in the paper as a joke.

01:04:34.230 --> 01:04:36.830
It's a very funny paper.

01:04:36.830 --> 01:04:39.440
Very silly paper, I should say.

01:04:39.440 --> 01:04:39.940
Right.

01:04:39.940 --> 01:04:41.315
Let me tell you
another wrapping.

01:04:52.010 --> 01:04:53.430
Chalk.

01:04:53.430 --> 01:04:54.440
The comb wrapping.

01:05:05.010 --> 01:05:07.930
Comb wrapping, we're going
to use the same idea.

01:05:07.930 --> 01:05:10.730
Again-- do I really
want to draw this again?

01:05:14.825 --> 01:05:19.670
I'm going to draw those petals,
but instead of connecting them

01:05:19.670 --> 01:05:21.610
at the north pole, we're
going to connect them

01:05:21.610 --> 01:05:23.350
along the equator.

01:05:23.350 --> 01:05:26.102
This is actually what
happens-- oh, no.

01:05:26.102 --> 01:05:28.560
This is not-- this connects
them at the north pole I guess,

01:05:28.560 --> 01:05:29.840
and it folds them in half.

01:05:29.840 --> 01:05:31.350
Whatever.

01:05:31.350 --> 01:05:35.060
But I have the equator
nicely denoted here.

01:05:35.060 --> 01:05:39.080
So I want to keep the equator
as a new stretched path.

01:05:39.080 --> 01:05:41.500
I want that to unfold straight.

01:05:41.500 --> 01:05:43.830
But then attached to
it perpendicularly

01:05:43.830 --> 01:05:46.690
are all these
petals which unfold.

01:05:46.690 --> 01:05:52.400
So the result looks like this.

01:05:52.400 --> 01:05:57.150
Here's the equatorial stretched
path and here are the petals.

01:05:57.150 --> 01:05:59.820
Petals are exactly the
same shapes as before,

01:05:59.820 --> 01:06:03.240
so we still have stretched
pads perpendicular like that.

01:06:03.240 --> 01:06:04.950
But it's a new way
to cover every point

01:06:04.950 --> 01:06:07.340
on the sphere with
stretched paths.

01:06:07.340 --> 01:06:09.370
It leads to the blue unfoldings.

01:06:09.370 --> 01:06:11.980
You can take the smallest
enclosing rectangle

01:06:11.980 --> 01:06:13.076
and you get the yellow.

01:06:17.024 --> 01:06:18.440
What do I want to
say about these?

01:06:22.090 --> 01:06:24.570
They're the same
area, of course.

01:06:24.570 --> 01:06:29.795
They look a lot like these
old cartograms, cartographs--

01:06:29.795 --> 01:06:34.200
whatever you call them--
unfoldings of the earth.

01:06:34.200 --> 01:06:35.410
I thought I brought an earth.

01:06:35.410 --> 01:06:37.080
Maybe we didn't bring the earth.

01:06:37.080 --> 01:06:40.349
A globe, that is.

01:06:40.349 --> 01:06:41.890
You've seen pictures
maybe like this.

01:06:41.890 --> 01:06:43.450
They're not unfolded
in the same way.

01:06:43.450 --> 01:06:46.080
They don't have stretched
paths that are perpendicular.

01:06:46.080 --> 01:06:48.250
They use some other
projection, so their petals

01:06:48.250 --> 01:06:49.650
are a different shape.

01:06:49.650 --> 01:06:51.810
And I'm not sure that
