Going through chocolate
like crazy here.

01:07:15.950 --> 01:07:19.180
This is the really
hard one to unfold.

01:07:19.180 --> 01:07:22.587
So here's one corner--
a little hard to see.

01:07:22.587 --> 01:07:23.920
Where's the equator going to be?

01:07:23.920 --> 01:07:27.270
I think the equator
is around here.

01:07:27.270 --> 01:07:28.690
That make sense?

01:07:28.690 --> 01:07:29.190
No.

01:07:29.190 --> 01:07:32.210
Actually it should be
perpendicular to that.

01:07:32.210 --> 01:07:34.619
Around here.

01:07:34.619 --> 01:07:35.910
This is a little harder to see.

01:07:39.600 --> 01:07:41.350
Here's a corner, actually.

01:07:41.350 --> 01:07:43.187
Tucked inside.

01:07:43.187 --> 01:07:45.020
I've been really curious
what kind of robots

01:07:45.020 --> 01:07:46.241
they have to do this.

01:07:46.241 --> 01:07:46.740
All right.

01:07:46.740 --> 01:07:47.531
Here's the equator.

01:07:47.531 --> 01:07:48.570
Now I can see it.

01:07:48.570 --> 01:07:50.420
So this-- the long
edge of the rectangle

01:07:50.420 --> 01:07:52.400
is wrapped around the equator.

01:07:52.400 --> 01:07:54.960
See it come off?

01:07:54.960 --> 01:07:57.720
And then the corners
are wrapped up

01:07:57.720 --> 01:08:02.130
against-- so there's
two-- well, yeah,

01:08:02.130 --> 01:08:04.810
these guys go on one side,
these guys go on the other.

01:08:04.810 --> 01:08:06.860
That's the short edge
of the rectangle.

01:08:06.860 --> 01:08:09.580
Now we can actually compute how
big these things are, right?

01:08:09.580 --> 01:08:14.780
So the-- where's the-- I
have a page about this.

01:08:14.780 --> 01:08:17.149
Not much.

01:08:17.149 --> 01:08:22.380
The vertical length,
that is one half equator.

01:08:22.380 --> 01:08:24.160
So that's pi.

01:08:24.160 --> 01:08:28.040
The horizontal length is 2pi.

01:08:28.040 --> 01:08:36.990
So this is Mirabell
rectangle, pi by 2pi.

01:08:36.990 --> 01:08:41.040
And we talked about
the Furst wrapping

01:08:41.040 --> 01:08:52.600
which, let's see, this length--
so this goes like this.

01:08:52.600 --> 01:08:55.090
So this is 2pi, right?

01:08:55.090 --> 01:08:57.649
The diagonal is 2pi.

01:08:57.649 --> 01:09:01.880
So that means this edge
length is root 2pi.

01:09:01.880 --> 01:09:02.439
By root 2pi.

01:09:05.359 --> 01:09:08.779
And magically-- I don't
really have a great reason why

01:09:08.779 --> 01:09:10.939
this should be the case
but-- well, maybe I

01:09:10.939 --> 01:09:13.760
do-- but these
have the same area.

01:09:13.760 --> 01:09:14.790
Both 2pi squared.

01:09:17.410 --> 01:09:19.479
Which is like 6pi.

01:09:19.479 --> 01:09:23.689
So better than 9ish pi, but
still not quite as good as

01:09:23.689 --> 01:09:26.250
4ish pi.

01:09:26.250 --> 01:09:29.210
I have some exact numbers.

01:09:29.210 --> 01:09:32.600
More exact numbers?

01:09:32.600 --> 01:09:35.220
Oh, I have the perimeters.

01:09:35.220 --> 01:09:39.170
So the first wrapping, the
perimeter is 5.7 times pi.

01:09:39.170 --> 01:09:41.540
And the Mirabell
wrapping is 6 times pi.

01:09:41.540 --> 01:09:43.415
So reasonable
savings in perimeter.

01:09:46.430 --> 01:09:48.410
2pi squared.

01:09:48.410 --> 01:09:52.359
The equilateral
triangle wrapping--

01:09:52.359 --> 01:09:55.710
that one in the top left--
instead of 2pi squared,

01:09:55.710 --> 01:10:00.810
it has area 1.9983pi squared.

01:10:00.810 --> 01:10:06.430
That's the 0.1% improvement.

01:10:06.430 --> 01:10:07.887
Amazing.

01:10:07.887 --> 01:10:08.720
This was a surprise.

01:10:08.720 --> 01:10:10.600
We thought it'd be a fair
amount better or worse

01:10:10.600 --> 01:10:11.641
or the same or something.

01:10:11.641 --> 01:10:13.140
But almost the same.

01:10:13.140 --> 01:10:16.100
It's not what we expected.

01:10:16.100 --> 01:10:18.680
Let's see.

01:10:18.680 --> 01:10:22.290
I want to go to packing.

01:10:22.290 --> 01:10:25.300
What if you want to do better
than those simple convex

01:10:25.300 --> 01:10:25.800
shapes?

01:10:25.800 --> 01:10:28.700
Yeah, equilateral triangles and
squares and rectangles pack.

01:10:28.700 --> 01:10:31.800
But what if I tried to-- what
if I allowed non-convex shapes?

01:10:31.800 --> 01:10:35.040
I still want to tile
the plane, so I'm

01:10:35.040 --> 01:10:36.990
going to lose some
material for that.

01:10:36.990 --> 01:10:39.320
I could add some of this
material to the blue guy, some

01:10:39.320 --> 01:10:41.750
to the purple, some to the red.

01:10:41.750 --> 01:10:43.980
You can compute the
area of this thing

01:10:43.980 --> 01:10:46.780
and it does a lot better than
the equilateral triangle even.

01:10:46.780 --> 01:10:48.190
So now we're getting down there.

01:10:48.190 --> 01:10:51.640
The perimeter goes up a
little bit, but not by much.

01:10:51.640 --> 01:10:57.690
Packing three petals gives
1.6 times pi squared.

01:10:57.690 --> 01:10:58.360
Getting better.

01:10:58.360 --> 01:11:01.240
By the way, 4pi-- because I'm
going to speak in pi squareds

01:11:01.240 --> 01:11:08.050
now-- 4pi is about
1.27pi squared.

01:11:08.050 --> 01:11:08.550
OK.

01:11:08.550 --> 01:11:10.620
So what we want
is 1.27pi squared.

01:11:10.620 --> 01:11:16.590
At this point, we're at
1.6033 times pi squared.

01:11:16.590 --> 01:11:19.820
The comb does better.

01:11:19.820 --> 01:11:23.530
In the limit, you don't
lose zero here in the limit,

01:11:23.530 --> 01:11:26.310
but you lose quite little.

01:11:26.310 --> 01:11:29.840
In the limit you get
1.333 times pi squared.

01:11:29.840 --> 01:11:31.089
Versus 1.27.

01:11:31.089 --> 01:11:31.880
That's pretty good.

01:11:31.880 --> 01:11:35.830
I think this is-- this is
what we should manufacture.

01:11:35.830 --> 01:11:36.330
Maybe.

01:11:36.330 --> 01:11:39.940
Of course, the perimeter
goes to infinity also.

01:11:39.940 --> 01:11:40.930
Slight problem.

01:11:40.930 --> 01:11:42.247
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:42.247 --> 01:11:44.080
PROFESSOR: You don't
lose zero in the limit.

01:11:44.080 --> 01:11:45.340
For awhile we thought we did.

01:11:45.340 --> 01:11:46.590
You'll have to think about it.

01:11:46.590 --> 01:11:47.298
It's not obvious.

01:11:49.760 --> 01:11:51.630
Really, we have this
two dimensional space.

01:11:51.630 --> 01:11:54.400
It's called the
Pareto curve or-- it's

01:11:54.400 --> 01:11:57.670
a plot of perimeter on
the x-axis versus area

01:11:57.670 --> 01:11:58.350
on the y-axis.

01:11:58.350 --> 01:11:59.770
We want both to be small.

01:12:02.470 --> 01:12:04.669
So two-source
wrapping, for example,

01:12:04.669 --> 01:12:05.960
is pretty good in both metrics.

01:12:05.960 --> 01:12:08.335
That's where you take the
Voronoi diagram, both the north

01:12:08.335 --> 01:12:09.920
and south pole.

01:12:09.920 --> 01:12:12.060
So you actually
have two disks-- one

01:12:12.060 --> 01:12:14.870
for the southern hemisphere, one
for the northern hemisphere--

01:12:14.870 --> 01:12:19.360
you get two disks and you
just attach them side by side.

01:12:19.360 --> 01:12:22.690
Although-- yeah.

01:12:22.690 --> 01:12:23.190
Let's see.

01:12:23.190 --> 01:12:24.940
What's this one?

01:12:24.940 --> 01:12:26.320
There's the Furst wrapping.

01:12:26.320 --> 01:12:28.194
So they're really good
in terms of perimeter.

01:12:28.194 --> 01:12:30.760
In fact, one of the
best perimeters we know.

01:12:30.760 --> 01:12:33.570
It's an open problem
how far left you can go.

01:12:33.570 --> 01:12:38.710
The stars are convex
hull of petal wrappings.

01:12:38.710 --> 01:12:41.540
Because the square was a convex
hull of a four petal wrapping.

01:12:41.540 --> 01:12:43.520
This is the convex of
the three petal wrapping.

01:12:43.520 --> 01:12:45.880
Now, that doesn't
actually tile, but it

01:12:45.880 --> 01:12:47.344
has the smallest
perimeter we now.

01:12:47.344 --> 01:12:49.010
So it's where you
take the three petals,

01:12:49.010 --> 01:12:50.801
but instead of completing
it to a triangle,

01:12:50.801 --> 01:12:54.770
you actually make the sharp
turn around the petal.

01:12:54.770 --> 01:13:02.790
So we have three
petals like this.

01:13:02.790 --> 01:13:05.460
And so the convex hull
is some tangent here.

01:13:05.460 --> 01:13:07.832
And then you follow
the petal for awhile.

01:13:07.832 --> 01:13:09.540
And then you take a
tangent, and then you

01:13:09.540 --> 01:13:12.550
follow the petal for a while,
and then you take a tangent.

01:13:12.550 --> 01:13:18.030
So that's the smallest
perimeter unfolding of a sphere

01:13:18.030 --> 01:13:19.450
that we know.

01:13:19.450 --> 01:13:20.050
Open problem.

01:13:20.050 --> 01:13:21.190
Can you do better?

01:13:21.190 --> 01:13:23.170
Can you get arbitrarily small?

01:13:23.170 --> 01:13:25.120
Probably not.

01:13:25.120 --> 01:13:26.800
Some isoperimetry problem.

01:13:26.800 --> 01:13:29.060
You can get arbitrarily
low area, arbitrarily

01:13:29.060 --> 01:13:32.100
close to the optimal of 4pi.

01:13:32.100 --> 01:13:35.770
That's like the strip wrapping.

01:13:35.770 --> 01:13:37.230
Let's see.

01:13:37.230 --> 01:13:38.560
So that's one limit.

01:13:38.560 --> 01:13:41.500
That corresponds to the limit
of petal or comb wrappings.

01:13:41.500 --> 01:13:43.750
Petal and comb wrappings,
if you don't take any hulls

01:13:43.750 --> 01:13:47.640
or anything, they are the same
area and the same perimeter.

01:13:47.640 --> 01:13:49.730
So I think out of
that you should

01:13:49.730 --> 01:13:52.150
be able to see why, in the
special case of the square

01:13:52.150 --> 01:13:53.900
and the rectangle, you
get the same stuff.

01:13:53.900 --> 01:13:57.750
There's a bijection
between all the parts.

01:13:57.750 --> 01:13:58.650
Not totally obvious.

01:13:58.650 --> 01:14:01.860
You have to dissect
a little bit.

01:14:01.860 --> 01:14:04.230
Mirabell wrappings,
they're not so good.

01:14:04.230 --> 01:14:04.890
What are those?

01:14:04.890 --> 01:14:07.880
The convex hull
of comb wrappings.

01:14:07.880 --> 01:14:08.880
So they're way out here.

01:14:08.880 --> 01:14:12.070
Clearly Furst is better.

01:14:12.070 --> 01:14:14.520
Here's the equilateral
triangle, which you can't tell,

01:14:14.520 --> 01:14:18.540
but it's slightly
below that dashed line.

01:14:18.540 --> 01:14:21.712
And pretty good perimeter but
not quite as good as Furst.

01:14:21.712 --> 01:14:24.170
So actually, probably, you
don't want to use the triangles.

01:14:24.170 --> 01:14:25.990
You prefer the lower perimeter.

01:14:25.990 --> 01:14:28.090
But this guy is interesting.

01:14:28.090 --> 01:14:29.550
Anyway, this is a fun space.

01:14:29.550 --> 01:14:31.735
What we kind of really
care about is-- this

01:14:31.735 --> 01:14:32.860
is called the Pareto curve.

01:14:32.860 --> 01:14:35.740
It's the, if I give you some
bound on perimeter, what's

01:14:35.740 --> 01:14:37.760
the smallest area I can get?

01:14:37.760 --> 01:14:39.540
This is the best
bound we know so far.

01:14:39.540 --> 01:14:42.560
And we know the Pareto
curves below this thing,

01:14:42.560 --> 01:14:44.480
but can you go lower?

01:14:44.480 --> 01:14:45.560
We don't know.

01:14:45.560 --> 01:14:48.550
So these are some fun examples,
but actually, the big questions

01:14:48.550 --> 01:14:51.050
are still pretty
much unsolved here.

01:14:51.050 --> 01:14:53.330
Even if you restrict
to-- I think

01:14:53.330 --> 01:14:56.700
it's fair to restrict to
wrappings of the sphere

01:14:56.700 --> 01:14:58.460
where every point
on the sphere gets

01:14:58.460 --> 01:15:01.850
covered by a stretched path.

01:15:01.850 --> 01:15:08.280
That seems like a nice,
natural class to think about.

01:15:12.490 --> 01:15:15.640
But we have no idea what
that hull space looks like.

01:15:15.640 --> 01:15:19.170
Can you do better than
these particular attempts?

01:15:19.170 --> 01:15:21.140
Looks like we're
doing pretty good,

01:15:21.140 --> 01:15:23.990
but we don't even know
how far left you can go.

01:15:23.990 --> 01:15:25.410
So a pretty neat question.

01:15:25.410 --> 01:15:26.790
And that is Mozart Kugel.

01:15:26.790 --> 01:15:29.630
Any questions?

01:15:29.630 --> 01:15:32.558
Other than, can I have some?

01:15:32.558 --> 01:15:33.950
AUDIENCE: Where can we get some?

01:15:33.950 --> 01:15:35.872
PROFESSOR: Where
can you get some.

01:15:35.872 --> 01:15:36.830
That's a good question.

01:15:36.830 --> 01:15:40.606
Most European airports
sell Mirabell.

01:15:40.606 --> 01:15:42.980
So if you're flying through
Europe, it's the place to go.

01:15:42.980 --> 01:15:46.420
Does anyone know if you
can get them locally?

01:15:46.420 --> 01:15:48.487
I think maybe.

01:15:48.487 --> 01:15:49.950
AUDIENCE: I think Cardullo's.

01:15:49.950 --> 01:15:51.720
PROFESSOR: Cardullo's
that's a good place.

01:15:51.720 --> 01:15:52.420
In Harvard Square.

01:15:52.420 --> 01:15:53.850
They have a lot of
imported chocolates.

01:15:53.850 --> 01:15:55.380
So, yeah, I think
they have Mirabell.

01:15:55.380 --> 01:15:55.855
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:15:55.855 --> 01:15:58.230
There's a lot of imported
chocolates and confectioneries

01:15:58.230 --> 01:15:59.760
in the Pru.

01:15:59.760 --> 01:16:01.260
PROFESSOR: In the
Prudential Center.

01:16:01.260 --> 01:16:02.200
All right.

01:16:02.200 --> 01:16:04.600
These I think you have
to go to Salzburg.

01:16:04.600 --> 01:16:06.590
Even in Austria
they're hard to get.

01:16:06.590 --> 01:16:08.462
So these are very special.

01:16:08.462 --> 01:16:12.191
I'll give Marty my second one.

01:16:12.191 --> 01:16:12.690
All right.

01:16:12.690 --> 01:16:14.117
That's all for today.

01:16:14.117 --> 01:16:16.700
Hey, there's one thing I forgot
to talk about in lecture which

01:16:16.700 --> 01:16:18.158
I think is really
cool so I'm going

01:16:18.158 --> 01:16:22.100
to add a little bit to
what we were talking about.

01:16:22.100 --> 01:16:23.840
We have all these
wrappings of the sphere

01:16:23.840 --> 01:16:26.350
but I never proved to that
they're actually contractive.

01:16:26.350 --> 01:16:31.790
How do you prove that all those
wrappings are contractive?

01:16:31.790 --> 01:16:36.620
Well, there's a cool theorem we
proved just for this purpose.

01:16:36.620 --> 01:16:45.055
I'll call it the Cauchy Arm
Lemma on a growing sphere.

01:16:48.130 --> 01:16:50.442
It's a nice little connection
to Cauchy's Arm Lemma

01:16:50.442 --> 01:16:55.930
which we talked about in the
context of Cauchy's rigidity

01:16:55.930 --> 01:16:58.920
theorem for polyhedral.

01:16:58.920 --> 01:17:00.630
Now, remember,
Cauchy's Arm Lemma

01:17:00.630 --> 01:17:04.980
is about you have
some convex chain--

01:17:04.980 --> 01:17:09.260
and actually it applies both
on the plane and the sphere.

01:17:09.260 --> 01:17:10.820
So we're thinking
of an open chain

01:17:10.820 --> 01:17:13.153
but we had the property that
even if you add the closing

01:17:13.153 --> 01:17:14.970
edge it's convex.

01:17:14.970 --> 01:17:17.520
And then we looked at
a flex of the chain

01:17:17.520 --> 01:17:20.500
where all of the
angles increased

01:17:20.500 --> 01:17:22.920
and we said, if all
the angles increase,

01:17:22.920 --> 01:17:25.676
then this distance
increases, the endpoint--

01:17:25.676 --> 01:17:27.550
the distance between
the endpoints increases.

01:17:27.550 --> 01:17:30.800
That's regular
Cauchy's Arm Lemma.

01:17:30.800 --> 01:17:34.430
But now I want to look at
not growing the angles,

01:17:34.430 --> 01:17:38.590
but growing the sphere
that the linkage lives on.

01:17:38.590 --> 01:17:40.640
So think of this in
the spherical case,

01:17:40.640 --> 01:17:46.570
which we'll-- imagine this
thing is on a sphere and now I

01:17:46.570 --> 01:17:52.030
transform it by taking a
larger sphere, larger radius,

01:17:52.030 --> 01:17:55.900
and drawing exactly the same
edge lengths and angles.

01:17:55.900 --> 01:17:57.600
Here, I'll draw it
a little bit curved

01:17:57.600 --> 01:18:03.710
because in reality these
edges are great circular arcs.

01:18:03.710 --> 01:18:06.800
So this edge length here
matches this length,

01:18:06.800 --> 01:18:09.990
this angle matches this
angle, this edge length

01:18:09.990 --> 01:18:12.350
matches this edge
length, and so on.

01:18:12.350 --> 01:18:15.680
But I draw it on
a bigger sphere.

01:18:15.680 --> 01:18:19.840
This theorem says, that the
distance between the endpoints

01:18:19.840 --> 01:18:23.280
will increase also in that case.

01:18:23.280 --> 01:18:25.500
So that's kind of neat.

01:18:25.500 --> 01:18:30.640
And in the limit, if you take a
ginormous sphere, all the way--

01:18:30.640 --> 01:18:35.170
if you take a really, really
big sphere, it becomes a plane.

01:18:35.170 --> 01:18:36.980
So if I take
something on a sphere

01:18:36.980 --> 01:18:42.910
and then I actually draw it on
the plane with the same angle--

01:18:42.910 --> 01:18:46.690
so this planar angle
matches this spherical angle

01:18:46.690 --> 01:18:50.270
and this length matches this
spherical length-- then,

01:18:50.270 --> 01:18:53.310
in particular, this
distance will increase.

01:18:53.310 --> 01:18:57.460
And in the reverse, if I
take a planar convex chain

01:18:57.460 --> 01:19:01.620
and I redraw it on some
sphere, the distance

01:19:01.620 --> 01:19:05.070
will go down provided
this thing is also convex.

01:19:05.070 --> 01:19:07.250
So that's the Lemma.

01:19:07.250 --> 01:19:09.882
Now, let me show you
how to use that to prove

01:19:09.882 --> 01:19:11.590
that all those wrappings
are contractive.

01:19:14.240 --> 01:19:16.073
It's really easy once
you have this Lemma.

01:19:19.080 --> 01:19:20.945
Let's start with
the source wrapping.

01:19:26.680 --> 01:19:29.570
So remember, we had a
sphere, the north pole,

01:19:29.570 --> 01:19:33.340
and we took all these shortest
paths from the north pole

01:19:33.340 --> 01:19:34.290
to the south pole.

01:19:34.290 --> 01:19:39.340
All of those lines-- I want
to claim that-- and when

01:19:39.340 --> 01:19:43.000
you unfold this you get a really
big disk and all those lines

01:19:43.000 --> 01:19:45.430
become straight.

01:19:45.430 --> 01:19:48.550
So what I need to show is that
between every pair of points,

01:19:48.550 --> 01:19:53.502
the distance decreases when
I go from flat to sphere.

01:19:53.502 --> 01:19:55.210
Which is exactly what
happened over here.

01:19:55.210 --> 01:19:59.500
I went from flat to the sphere,
this distance decreased.

01:19:59.500 --> 01:20:01.220
So that's how it's
going to be useful.

01:20:01.220 --> 01:20:06.680
If I take two points, like,
say, this point and this point.

01:20:06.680 --> 01:20:07.710
Any two points.

01:20:07.710 --> 01:20:13.940
They live on one of these
spokes that goes to the center.

01:20:13.940 --> 01:20:16.040
So draw those two
segments to the center

01:20:16.040 --> 01:20:17.340
which was the north pole here.

01:20:17.340 --> 01:20:20.740
So if I take the corresponding
two points up here,

01:20:20.740 --> 01:20:24.690
I'm looking at that
path and that path.

01:20:24.690 --> 01:20:28.146
Well, that's a convex chain
and the distance between them--

01:20:28.146 --> 01:20:31.260
between those two points that
I started with, say, x and y,

01:20:31.260 --> 01:20:36.270
is exactly the closing
distance of that convex chain.

01:20:36.270 --> 01:20:38.650
So here's a convex chain,
it matches the angles

01:20:38.650 --> 01:20:41.200
and the lengths of this
convex chain and the plane.

01:20:41.200 --> 01:20:45.160
Therefore, this distance is
larger than this distance.

01:20:45.160 --> 01:20:46.980
And so this is a
contractive map because it

01:20:46.980 --> 01:20:49.240
works for any two
points x and y.

01:20:49.240 --> 01:20:51.150
So that's the source wrapping.

01:20:51.150 --> 01:20:54.470
With slightly more effort,
slightly more interesting

01:20:54.470 --> 01:20:59.550
example, is the petal wrappings.

01:20:59.550 --> 01:21:01.865
So think about one petal.

01:21:04.410 --> 01:21:08.550
So let's say I just take-- in
fact, just think about half

01:21:08.550 --> 01:21:10.420
of a petal.

01:21:10.420 --> 01:21:14.240
So we had a petal look
something like that

01:21:14.240 --> 01:21:16.960
going to the south pole here.

01:21:16.960 --> 01:21:23.340
And so we bisected this thing
and then we took lots of ribs

01:21:23.340 --> 01:21:24.270
like that.

01:21:24.270 --> 01:21:25.580
So that's one half petal.

01:21:29.610 --> 01:21:32.760
So when you unfold,
it looks like this.

01:21:35.460 --> 01:21:37.890
Take any two points
on the half petal.

01:21:37.890 --> 01:21:40.920
I'll show, first of all, that
the half petal is contractive.

01:21:40.920 --> 01:21:44.710
So I take two points, say,
this one and this one,

01:21:44.710 --> 01:21:47.170
call them x and y.

01:21:47.170 --> 01:21:52.100
Now I take this rib,
this rib and this rib.

01:21:52.100 --> 01:21:54.950
Those are the
stretched paths again.

01:21:54.950 --> 01:21:57.120
They map to whatever up here.

01:21:57.120 --> 01:21:59.880
Again, it's a
convex chain and so

01:21:59.880 --> 01:22:02.760
this distance increases
when you go to the sphere

01:22:02.760 --> 01:22:05.850
because it's convex
in both scenarios.

01:22:05.850 --> 01:22:06.800
So that's half petals.

01:22:06.800 --> 01:22:08.830
Now, when you worry
about a full petal

01:22:08.830 --> 01:22:11.038
and you want to show the
whole wrapping is expansive,

01:22:11.038 --> 01:22:14.940
you actually use a
different method.

01:22:14.940 --> 01:22:17.850
So let's say we take
a whole petal here.

01:22:20.510 --> 01:22:22.880
And I want to show not
only any pair of points

01:22:22.880 --> 01:22:27.370
within a single half petal
contract but, in fact,

01:22:27.370 --> 01:22:30.440
any two vertices, any
two points contract.

01:22:30.440 --> 01:22:33.190
So I'm going to take x
and some other point.

01:22:33.190 --> 01:22:35.000
Now I'll call it z.

01:22:35.000 --> 01:22:38.360
If I did the-- just looked
at the stretched paths,

01:22:38.360 --> 01:22:39.560
that's no longer convex.

01:22:39.560 --> 01:22:41.100
I can't use the same trick.

01:22:41.100 --> 01:22:43.400
But here's a new trick.

01:22:43.400 --> 01:22:47.075
I take a straight line, a
shortest path from x to z,

01:22:47.075 --> 01:22:50.570
which gives me a new
point y in the middle.

01:22:50.570 --> 01:22:53.070
Now I know that this
distance contracts

01:22:53.070 --> 01:22:55.700
because that's within
a single half petal.

01:22:55.700 --> 01:22:58.090
So by the previous
argument, and by looking

01:22:58.090 --> 01:23:01.820
at that little chain, I
know by this Arm Lemma

01:23:01.820 --> 01:23:04.830
that distance contracts, I know
that this distance contracts.

01:23:04.830 --> 01:23:06.840
So what about the
whole distance?

01:23:06.840 --> 01:23:09.980
Well, if I look at the
distance from x to z--

01:23:09.980 --> 01:23:15.790
that's what I care about--
let's say, in the plane,

01:23:15.790 --> 01:23:18.460
this equals the sum
of those distances.

01:23:18.460 --> 01:23:20.210
Because we drew a
straight line, it

01:23:20.210 --> 01:23:23.400
equals the distance from x to y
plus the distance from y to z.

01:23:26.360 --> 01:23:29.020
Now, I mapped these
onto the sphere,

01:23:29.020 --> 01:23:32.540
call that d prime is
the spherical distance.

01:23:32.540 --> 01:23:35.320
I know that when I look
at d prime I contract.

01:23:35.320 --> 01:23:39.330
So d prime of xy is going
to be smaller for xy,

01:23:39.330 --> 01:23:43.000
it's going to be smaller for yz.

01:23:43.000 --> 01:23:44.930
What I really care
about is the distance

01:23:44.930 --> 01:23:47.800
of the sphere between x and z.

01:23:47.800 --> 01:23:50.840
But this is the
triangle inequality.

01:23:50.840 --> 01:23:57.570
If you have a triangle xyz,
the distance from x to z

01:23:57.570 --> 01:24:00.100
is always, at most,
the distance from x

01:24:00.100 --> 01:24:01.980
to y plus the
distance from y to z.

01:24:01.980 --> 01:24:03.841
That holds in any metric space.

01:24:03.841 --> 01:24:05.590
So, in particular, it
holds on the sphere.

01:24:05.590 --> 01:24:06.714
So this is sort of trivial.

01:24:06.714 --> 01:24:08.550
This is triangle inequality.

01:24:08.550 --> 01:24:12.950
And this was the contractiveness
that we already prove.

01:24:12.950 --> 01:24:14.250
And this is just equal.

01:24:14.250 --> 01:24:16.060
And so we get that
the new distance

01:24:16.060 --> 01:24:18.550
is a contraction of
the old distance.

01:24:18.550 --> 01:24:20.110
So that works on a full petal.

01:24:20.110 --> 01:24:22.150
It actually-- this
exact same technique

01:24:22.150 --> 01:24:25.040
works if you have a
full petal unfolding.

01:24:25.040 --> 01:24:27.440
Maybe you have
something like this.

01:24:27.440 --> 01:24:33.170
And you take-- finish it off--
you take two points anywhere

01:24:33.170 --> 01:24:36.230
on any two petals,
like here and here, you

01:24:36.230 --> 01:24:38.940
take the shortest
path between them

01:24:38.940 --> 01:24:40.820
and again, you
could argue, well,

01:24:40.820 --> 01:24:44.015
this is going to contract
because it is in a single half

01:24:44.015 --> 01:24:45.890
petal, this is going to
contract because it's

01:24:45.890 --> 01:24:47.150
in a single have petal.

01:24:47.150 --> 01:24:49.770
Therefore, that sum
will also contract

01:24:49.770 --> 01:24:51.630
by exactly the same argument.

01:24:51.630 --> 01:24:53.960
And you can use that for
the comb wrapping too.

01:24:53.960 --> 01:24:55.870
This is kind of neat
with this little Lemma

01:24:55.870 --> 01:24:59.370
about growing spheres and
showing the distances increase,

01:24:59.370 --> 01:25:01.880
you get to prove that all of
these wrappings are contractive

01:25:01.880 --> 01:25:03.754
and therefore all these
things I was claiming

01:25:03.754 --> 01:25:05.090
were working really do work.

01:25:05.090 --> 01:25:09.170
You can formalize that
in a simple little way.

